# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ahklun-mountains
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] The **Ahklun Mountains** are located in the northeast section of the Togiak National Wildlife Refuge in southwest Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] They extend southwest from the Kanektok and Narogurum Rivers to Hagemeister Strait and Kuskokwim Bay and support the only existing glaciers in western Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] They are the highest Alaskan mountain range west of the Alaska Range and north of the Alaska Peninsula: some summits in the range have many glaciers.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] To the west is the Kuskokwim River and to the east are the Bristol Bay lowlands.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] The Ahklun Mountains have many lakes, some more than 1,300 feet (400 m) deep.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] The mountains cover approximately 80 percent of the Togiak National Wildlife Refuge.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] The refuge also contains tundra and coastal plains.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] The Ahklun Mountains are dominated by alpine tundra, heath, and barrens, while moist sedge-tussock meadows occur in valley bottoms.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] Black spruce forest occurs on some hills and ridges.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] Forests of white spruce, paper birch, and alder cover the low hills along the major rivers.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] Blackpoll warblers are common breeders in conifer stands in river valleys.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] Beaver are abundant, supporting a large annual harvest.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] Sockeye salmon are the most abundant fish.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] Chum, king, silver salmon, and rainbow trout are also numerous.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] The average annual precipitation ranges from 19 to 25 inches (480 to 640 mm), while the average annual temperature ranges from 29 to 33 °F (−2 to 1 °C).
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] The growing season extends approximately from May 15 to September 10.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] The glaciers were first mapped by the U.S.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] Geological Survey, who used photogrammetry methods based on a 1972 series of aerial photos, revealing the presence of 116 glaciers.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] In 2006, 109 of these glaciers were resurveyed with the existence of 97 verified and 12 thought to have disappeared.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] This showed that over just three decades there had been a large decrease in the amount of land area covered by glacial ice in these mountains.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] The scientific community has long recognized the importance of glaciers as indicators of climatic change.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] In 2015, researchers analyzed aerial and satellite images from 1957, 1984, and 2009.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] They found that 10 out of 109 of the glaciers of the Ahklun Mountains originally mapped by the U.S.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] Geological Survey in the 1970s had completely disappeared.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] They also compared the size of the glaciers using aerial photographs and satellite images and found that the glaciers had lost about 50 percent of their total area.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] At this rate of melting, they predict that all of the glaciers in the Ahklun Mountains will be gone by the end of this century.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] Geological evidence show that during the Pleistocene era there were repeated glaciations that have carved out a large number of valley troughs.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] On the eastern side, these troughs contain networks of glacial lakes, some that are over 1,300 feet (400 m) deep and are dammed by terminal moraines.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] On the southern and western side, the valleys are broader and are interspersed with rolling uplands pierced by rugged massifs.
[src:ahklun-mountains/ahklun-mountains] In the lowlands, areas not reached by the glaciation, the principal geographic features are the moraines and ridges formed by thrusting ice.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska is the largest U.S. state by area—comprising more total area than the next three largest states of Texas, California, and Montana combined—and is the world's largest semi-exclave and seventh-largest subnational division.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] With a population of 740,133 in 2024, it is the third-least populous and most sparsely populated state in the U.S., but the most populous territory in North America located mostly north of the 60th parallel, with more than quadruple the combined populations of Northern Canada and Greenland.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska contains the four largest cities in the United States by area, including the state capital, Juneau.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska's most populous city is Anchorage, and approximately half the state's residents live within its metropolitan area.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Indigenous people have lived in Alaska for thousands of years, and it is widely believed that the region served as the entry point for the initial settlement of the Americas by way of the Bering land bridge.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The Russian Empire was the first to actively colonize the area beginning in the 18th century, eventually establishing Russian America, which spanned most of the current state and promoted and maintained a native Alaskan Creole population.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The expense and logistical difficulty of maintaining this distant possession prompted its sale to the U.S. in 1867 for US$7.2 million, equivalent to $166 million in 2025.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The area went through several administrative changes before becoming organized as a territory on May 11, 1912.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] It was admitted as the 49th state of the U.S. on January 3, 1959.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] An abundance of natural resources—including commercial fishing and the extraction of natural gas and oil—has enabled Alaska to have one of the highest per capita incomes in the United States, despite having one of the smallest economies.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Armed Forces bases and tourism also contribute to the economy; more than half of Alaska is federally owned, containing national forests, national parks, and wildlife refuges.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] It is among the most irreligious states and one of the first to legalize recreational marijuana.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska has the highest proportion of Native Americans of any U.S. state, at 22 percent.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The name *Alaska* (Russian: Аля́ска, romanized: *Aljáska*) was introduced during the Russian colonial period when it was used to refer to the Alaska Peninsula.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] It was derived from an Aleut-language idiom, *alaxsxaq*, meaning 'the mainland' or, more literally, 'the object towards which the action of the sea is directed'.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Numerous Indigenous peoples occupied Alaska for thousands of years before the arrival of European peoples to the area.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Linguistic and DNA studies done here have provided evidence for the settlement of North America by way of the Bering land bridge.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] At the Upward Sun River site in the Tanana Valley in Alaska, remains of a six-week-old infant were found.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The baby's DNA showed that she belonged to a population that was genetically separate from other Native groups present elsewhere in the New World at the end of the Pleistocene.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Ben Potter, the University of Alaska Fairbanks archaeologist who unearthed the remains at the Upward Sun River site in 2013, named this new group Ancient Beringian.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The Tlingit people developed a society with a matrilineal kinship system of property inheritance and descent in what is present Southeast Alaska, along with parts of British Columbia and the Yukon.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Also in the Southeast were the Haida, now well known for their unique arts.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The Tsimshian people came to Alaska from British Columbia in 1887, when President Grover Cleveland, and later the U.S.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Congress, granted them permission to settle on Annette Island and found the town of Metlakatla, Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] All three of these peoples, as well as other Indigenous peoples of the Pacific Northwest Coast, experienced smallpox outbreaks from the late 18th through the mid-19th century, with the most devastating epidemics occurring in the 1830s and 1860s, resulting in high fatalities and social disruption.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Some researchers believe the first Russian settlement in Alaska was established in the 17th century.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] According to this hypothesis, in 1648 several koches of Semyon Dezhnyov's expedition came ashore in Alaska by storm and founded this settlement.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] This hypothesis is based on the testimony of Chukchi geographer Nikolai Daurkin, who had visited Alaska in 1764–1765 and who had reported on a village on the Kheuveren River, populated by "bearded men" who "pray to the icons".
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Some modern researchers associate the Kheuveren with the Koyuk River.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The first European vessel to reach Alaska is generally held to be the *St.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Gabriel* under the authority of the surveyor M.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Fyodorov on August 21, 1732, during an expedition of Siberian Cossack A.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Shestakov and Russian explorer Dmitry Pavlutsky (1729–1735).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Another European contact with Alaska occurred in 1741, when Vitus Bering led an expedition for the Russian Navy aboard the *St.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] After his crew returned to Russia with sea otter pelts judged to be the finest fur in the world, small associations of fur traders began to sail from the shores of Siberia toward the Aleutian Islands.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The first permanent European settlement was founded in 1784.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] From 1774 to 1800, Spain sent several expeditions to Alaska to assert its claim over the Pacific Northwest, which it considered part of New Spain, administered from Mexico City, Mexico.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In 1789, a Spanish settlement and fort were built in Nootka Sound.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] These expeditions gave names to places such as Valdez, Bucareli Sound, and Cordova.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Later, the Russian-American Company carried out an expanded colonization program during the early-to-mid-19th century.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Sitka, renamed New Archangel from 1804 to 1867, on Baranof Island in the Alexander Archipelago in what is now Southeast Alaska, became the capital of Russian America.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] It remained the capital after the colony was transferred to the United States.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The Russians never fully colonized Alaska, and the colony was never very profitable.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Evidence of Russian settlement in names and churches survives throughout southeastern Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Seward, the United States Secretary of State under President Andrew Johnson, negotiated the Alaska Purchase, referred to pejoratively as Seward's Folly, with the Russians for $7.2 million.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Russian emperor Alexander II also planned the sale.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The purchase was made on March 30, 1867.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Six months later the commissioners arrived in Sitka and the formal transfer was arranged.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The flag-raising took place at Fort Sitka on October 18, 1867.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In the ceremony, 250 uniformed U.S. soldiers marched to the governor's house at "Castle Hill", where the Russian troops lowered the Russian flag and the U.S. flag was raised.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] This event is celebrated as Alaska Day, a legal holiday on October 18.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska was loosely governed by the military initially and was administered as a district starting in 1884, with a governor appointed by the United States president.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] A federal district court was headquartered in Sitka.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] For most of Alaska's first decade under the United States flag, Sitka was the only community inhabited by American settlers.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] They organized "a provisional city government", which was Alaska's first municipal government, but not in a legal sense.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Legislation allowing Alaskan communities to legally incorporate as cities arrived in 1900, and home rule for cities was extremely limited or unavailable until statehood took effect in 1959.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Starting in the 1890s and stretching in some places to the early 1910s, gold rushes in Alaska and the nearby Yukon Territory brought thousands of miners and settlers to Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In 1912, Alaska was incorporated as an organized territory.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska's capital, which had been in Sitka until 1906, was moved north to Juneau.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Construction of the Alaska Governor's Mansion began that same year.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] European immigrants from Norway and Sweden also settled in southeast Alaska, where they entered the fishing and logging industries.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] During World War II, the Aleutian Islands Campaign focused on Attu, Agattu and Kiska, all of which were occupied by the Empire of Japan.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] During the Japanese occupation, an American civilian and two United States Navy personnel were killed at Attu and Kiska respectively, and almost 50 Aleut civilians and eight sailors were interned in Japan.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] About half of the Aleuts died during the period of internment.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Unalaska/Dutch Harbor and Adak became significant bases for the United States Army, United States Army Air Forces and United States Navy.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The United States Lend-Lease program involved flying American warplanes through Canada to Fairbanks and then Nome.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Soviet pilots took possession of these aircraft, ferrying them to fight the German invasion of the Soviet Union.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The construction of military bases contributed to the population growth of some Alaskan cities.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Statehood for Alaska was an important cause of James Wickersham early in his tenure as a congressional delegate.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Decades later, the statehood movement gained its first real momentum following a territorial referendum in 1946.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The Alaska Statehood Committee and Alaska's Constitutional Convention soon followed.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Statehood supporters also found themselves fighting major battles against political foes, mostly in the U.S.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska was officially proclaimed a state on January 3, 1959.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] On March 27, 1964, the Good Friday earthquake killed 133 people and destroyed several villages and portions of large coastal communities, mainly by the resultant tsunamis and landslides.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] It was the fourth-most-powerful earthquake in recorded history, with a moment magnitude of 9.2, more than a thousand times as powerful as the 1989 San Francisco earthquake.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The time of day (5:36 pm), time of year (spring) and location of the epicenter were all cited as factors in potentially sparing thousands of lives, particularly in Anchorage.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The Good Friday earthquake lasted 4 minutes and 38 seconds.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Six hundred miles (970 km) of fault ruptured at once and moved up to 60 ft (18 m), releasing about 500 years of stress buildup.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Soil liquefaction, fissures, landslides, and other ground failures caused major structural damage in several communities and much damage to property.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Anchorage sustained great destruction or damage to many inadequately earthquake-engineered houses, buildings, and infrastructure (paved streets, sidewalks, water and sewer mains, electrical systems, and other human-made equipment), particularly in the several landslide zones along Knik Arm.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Two hundred miles (320 km) southwest, some areas near Kodiak were permanently raised by 30 feet (9 m).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Southeast of Anchorage, areas around the head of Turnagain Arm near Girdwood and Portage dropped as much as 8 feet (2.4 m), requiring reconstruction and fill to raise the Seward Highway above the new high tide mark.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In Prince William Sound, Port Valdez suffered a massive underwater landslide, resulting in the deaths of 32 people between the collapse of the Valdez city harbor and docks, and inside the ship that was docked there at the time.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Nearby, a 27-foot (8.2 m) tsunami destroyed the village of Chenega, killing 23 of the 68 people who lived there; survivors out-ran the wave, climbing to high ground.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Post-quake tsunamis severely affected Whittier, Seward, Kodiak, and other Alaskan communities, as well as people and property in British Columbia, Washington, Oregon, and California.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Tsunamis also caused damage in Hawaii and Japan.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Evidence of motion directly related to the earthquake was also reported from Florida and Texas.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska had never experienced a major disaster in a highly populated area before and had very limited resources for dealing with the effects of such an event.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In Anchorage, at the urging of geologist Lidia Selkregg, the City of Anchorage and the Alaska State Housing Authority appointed a team of 40 scientists, including geologists, soil scientists, and engineers, to assess the damage done by the earthquake to the city.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The team, called the Engineering and Geological Evaluation Group, was headed by Ruth A.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Schmidt, a geology professor at the University of Alaska Anchorage.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The team of scientists came into conflict with local developers and downtown business owners who wanted to immediately rebuild; the scientists wanted to identify future dangers to ensure that the rebuilt infrastructure would be safe.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The team produced a report on May 8, 1964, just a little more than a month after the earthquake.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The United States military, which has a large active presence in Alaska, also stepped in to assist within moments of the end of the quake.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Army rapidly re-established communications with the lower 48 states, deployed troops to assist the citizens of Anchorage, and dispatched a convoy to Valdez.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] On the advice of military and civilian leaders, President Lyndon B.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Johnson declared all of Alaska a major disaster area the day after the quake.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Coast Guard deployed ships to isolated coastal communities to assist with immediate needs.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Bad weather and poor visibility hampered air rescue and observation efforts the day after the quake, but on Sunday the 29th the situation improved and rescue helicopters and observation aircraft were deployed.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] A military airlift immediately began shipping relief supplies to Alaska, eventually delivering 2,570,000 pounds (1,170,000 kg) of food and other supplies.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Broadcast journalist, Genie Chance, assisted in recovery and relief efforts, staying on the KENI air waves over Anchorage for more than 24 continuous hours as the voice of calm from her temporary post within the Anchorage Public Safety Building.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] She was effectively designated as the public safety officer by the city's police chief.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Army Corps of Engineers led the effort to rebuild roads, clear debris, and establish new townsites for communities that had been completely destroyed, at a cost of $110 million.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The West Coast and Alaska Tsunami Warning Center was formed as a direct response to the disaster.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Federal disaster relief funds paid for reconstruction as well as financially supporting the devastated infrastructure of Alaska's government, spending hundreds of millions of dollars that helped keep Alaska financially solvent until the discovery of massive oil deposits at Prudhoe Bay.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Defense Department, the Alaska National Guard founded the Alaska Division of Emergency Services to respond to any future disasters.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The 1968 discovery of oil at Prudhoe Bay and the 1977 completion of the Trans-Alaska Pipeline System led to an oil boom.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Royalty revenues from oil have funded large state budgets from 1980 onward.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Oil production was not the only economic value of Alaska's land.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Alaska discovered tourism as an important source of revenue.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Tourism became popular after World War II when military personnel stationed in the region returned home praising its natural splendor.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The Alcan Highway, built during the war, and the Alaska Marine Highway System, completed in 1963, made the state more accessible than before.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Tourism has become increasingly important in Alaska, and today more than 1.4 million people visit the state each year.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] With tourism more vital to the economy, environmentalism rose in importance.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Because of the Act, Alaska now contains two-thirds of all American national parklands.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Today, more than half of Alaskan land is owned by the Federal Government.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In 1989, the *Exxon Valdez* hit a reef in the Prince William Sound, spilling more than 11 million gallons (42 megalitres) of crude oil over 1,100 miles (1,800 km) of coastline.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Today, the battle between philosophies of development and conservation is seen in the contentious debate over oil drilling in the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge and the proposed Pebble Mine.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Located at the northwest corner of North America very near to Asia, Alaska is the northernmost and westernmost state in the United States, but also has the most easterly longitude in the United States because the Aleutian Islands extend into the Eastern Hemisphere.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska is the only non-contiguous U.S. state on continental North America; about 500 miles (800 km) of Canadian territory consisting of British Columbia (in Canada) separates Alaska from Washington.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] It is technically part of the continental U.S., but is not usually included in the colloquial use of the term; Alaska is not part of the contiguous U.S., often called "the Lower 48".
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The capital city, Juneau, is situated on the mainland of the North American continent but is not connected by road to the rest of the North American highway system.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The largest lake in Alaska is Lake Illiamna.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska is bordered by Canada's Yukon and British Columbia to the east (making it the only state to border only a Canadian territory); the Gulf of Alaska and the Pacific Ocean to the south and southwest; the Bering Sea, Bering Strait, and Chukchi Sea to the west; and the Arctic Ocean to the north.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska's territorial waters touch Russia's territorial waters in the Bering Strait, as the Russian Big Diomede Island and Alaskan Little Diomede Island are only 3 miles (4.8 km) apart.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska has a longer coastline than all the other U.S. states combined.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] At 663,268 square miles (1,717,856 km2) in total area, Alaska is by far the largest state in the United States.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska is more than twice the size of the second-largest U.S. state (Texas), and it is larger than the next three largest states (Texas, California, and Montana) combined.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska is the seventh largest subnational division in the world.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] If it was an independent nation, it would be the 18th largest country in the world; almost the same size as Iran.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] With its myriad islands, Alaska has nearly 34,000 miles (55,000 km) of tidal shoreline.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The Aleutian Islands chain extends west from the southern tip of the Alaska Peninsula.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Many active volcanoes are found in the Aleutians and in coastal regions.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Unimak Island, for example, is home to Mount Shishaldin, which is an occasionally smoldering volcano that rises to 10,000 feet (3,000 m) above the North Pacific.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The chain of volcanoes extends to Mount Spurr, west of Anchorage on the mainland.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Geologists have identified Alaska as part of Wrangellia, a large region consisting of multiple states and Canadian provinces in the Pacific Northwest, which is actively undergoing continent building.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] One of the world's largest tides occurs in Turnagain Arm, just south of Anchorage, where tidal differences can be more than 35 feet (10.7 m).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska has more than 409,000 natural lakes at least one hectare or bigger.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Marshlands and wetland permafrost cover 188,320 square miles (487,700 km2) (mostly in northern, western and southwest flatlands).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Glacier ice covers about 28,957 square miles (75,000 km2) of Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The Bering Glacier is the largest glacier in North America, covering 2,008 square miles (5,200 km2) alone.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The most populous region of Alaska contains Anchorage, the Matanuska-Susitna Valley and the Kenai Peninsula.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Rural, mostly unpopulated areas south of the Alaska Range and west of the Wrangell Mountains also fall within the definition of South Central, as do the Prince William Sound area and the communities of Cordova and Valdez.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Also referred to as the Panhandle or Inside Passage, this is the region of Alaska closest to the contiguous states.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] As such, this was where most of the initial non-indigenous settlement occurred in the years following the Alaska Purchase.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The region is dominated by the Alexander Archipelago as well as the Tongass National Forest, the largest national forest in the United States.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] It contains the state capital Juneau, the former capital Sitka, and Ketchikan, at one time Alaska's largest city.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The Alaska Marine Highway provides a vital surface transportation link throughout the area and country, as only three communities (Haines, Hyder and Skagway) enjoy direct connections to the contiguous North American road system.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The Interior is the largest region of Alaska; much of it is uninhabited wilderness.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Fairbanks is the only large city in the region.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Denali National Park and Preserve is located here.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Denali, federally designated as Mount McKinley, is the highest mountain in North America and is also located here.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The North Slope is mostly tundra peppered with small villages.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The area is known for its massive reserves of crude oil and contains both the National Petroleum Reserve–Alaska and the Prudhoe Bay Oil Field.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The city of Utqiaġvik, formerly known as Barrow, is the northernmost city in the United States and is located here.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The Northwest Arctic area, anchored by Kotzebue and also containing the Kobuk River valley, is often considered part of this region.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The respective Inupiat of the North Slope and of the Northwest Arctic seldom consider themselves to be one people.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Southwest Alaska is a sparsely inhabited region stretching some 500 miles (800 km) inland from the Bering Sea.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Most of the population lives along the coast.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Kodiak Island is also located in the Southwest.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The massive Yukon–Kuskokwim Delta, one of the largest river deltas in the world, is here.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Portions of the Alaska Peninsula are considered part of the Southwest, with the Aleutian Islands often (but not always) being grouped in as well.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] While primarily part of Southwest Alaska when grouped economically, the Aleutian islands are sometimes recognized as an alternate group from the rest of the region due to the geographic separation from the continent.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] More than 300 small volcanic islands make up this chain, which stretches more than 1,200 miles (1,900 km) into the Pacific Ocean.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Some of these islands fall in the Eastern Hemisphere, but the International Date Line was drawn west of 180° to keep the whole state, and thus the entire North American continent, within the same legal day.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Two of the islands, Attu and Kiska, were occupied by Japanese forces during World War II.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] As of 2023 the United States Bureau of Land Management manages 290 million surface and subsurface acres as public lands, including a multitude of national forests, national parks, national wildlife refuges, and federal mineral estate land.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Of these, the Bureau of Land Management manages 87 million acres (35 million hectares), or 23.8% of the state.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The Arctic National Wildlife Refuge is managed by the United States Fish and Wildlife Service.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] It is the world's largest wildlife refuge, comprising 16 million acres (6.5 million hectares).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Of the remaining land area, the state of Alaska owns 101 million acres (41 million hectares), its entitlement under the Alaska Statehood Act.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] A portion of that acreage is occasionally ceded to the organized boroughs presented above, under the statutory provisions pertaining to newly formed boroughs.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Smaller portions are set aside for rural subdivisions and other homesteading-related opportunities.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] These are not very popular due to the often remote and roadless locations.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The University of Alaska, as a land grant university, also owns substantial acreage which it manages independently.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Another 44 million acres (18 million hectares) are owned by 12 regional, and scores of local, Native corporations created under the Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act (ANCSA) of 1971.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Regional Native corporation Doyon, Limited often promotes itself as the largest private landowner in Alaska in advertisements and other communications.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Provisions of ANCSA allowing the corporations' land holdings to be sold on the open market starting in 1991 were repealed before they could take effect.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Effectively, the corporations hold title (including subsurface title in many cases, a privilege denied to individual Alaskans) but cannot sell the land.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Individual Native allotments are sold on the open market.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Various private interests own the remaining land, totaling about one percent of the state.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska is, by a large margin, the state with the smallest percentage of private land ownership when Native corporation holdings are excluded.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The Alaska Heritage Resources Survey (AHRS) is a restricted inventory of all reported historic and prehistoric sites within the U.S. state of Alaska; it is maintained by the Office of History and Archaeology.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The survey's inventory of cultural resources includes objects, structures, buildings, sites, districts, and travel ways, with a general provision that they are more than fifty years old.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] As of 31 January 2012, more than 35,000 sites have been reported.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Unlike most of U.S. states, Alaska is not divided into counties.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Similarly to Louisiana's parishes, it is divided into *boroughs*.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Delegates to the Alaska Constitutional Convention wanted to avoid the pitfalls of the traditional county system and adopted their own unique model.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Many of the more densely populated parts of the state are part of Alaska's 16 boroughs, which function somewhat similarly to counties in other states.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Unlike county-equivalents in the other states, the boroughs do not cover the state's entire land area.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The area not part of any borough is referred to as the Unorganized Borough.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The Unorganized Borough has no government of its own, but the U.S.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Census Bureau in cooperation with the state divided the Unorganized Borough into 11 census areas solely for the purposes of statistical analysis and presentation.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] A *recording district* is a mechanism for management of the public record in Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The state is divided into 34 recording districts which are centrally administered under a state recorder.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] All recording districts use the same acceptance criteria, fee schedule, etc., for accepting documents into the public record.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Whereas many U.S. states use a three-tiered system of decentralization—state/county/township—most of Alaska uses two tiers—state/borough.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Owing to the low population density, most of the land is located in the Unorganized Borough.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] As the name implies, it has no intermediate borough government but is administered directly by the state government.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In 2000, 57.71% of Alaska's area has this status, with 13.05% of the population.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In 1975, Anchorage merged the city government with the Greater Anchorage Area Borough to form the Municipality of Anchorage, containing the city proper and the communities of Eagle River, Chugiak, Peters Creek, Girdwood, Bird, and Indian.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Fairbanks has a separate borough (the Fairbanks North Star Borough) and municipality (the City of Fairbanks).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska's most populous city is Anchorage, home to 291,247 people in 2020.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The richest location in Alaska by per capita income is Denali ($42,245).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Yakutat, Sitka, Juneau, and Anchorage are the four largest cities in the U.S. by area.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In the 2020 United States census, Alaska has 355 incorporated cities and census-designated places (CDPs).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The tally of cities includes four unified municipalities, essentially the equivalent of a consolidated city–county.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The majority of these communities are located in the rural expanse of Alaska known as "The Bush" and are unconnected to that contiguous North American road network.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The table at the bottom of this section lists the 100 largest cities and census-designated places in Alaska, in population order.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Of Alaska's 2020 U.S. census population figure of 733,391, 16,655 people, or 2.27% of the population, did not live in an incorporated city or census-designated place.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Approximately three-quarters of that figure were people who live in urban and suburban neighborhoods on the outskirts of the city limits of Ketchikan, Kodiak, Palmer and Wasilla.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] CDPs have not been established for these areas by the United States Census Bureau.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Seven CDPs were established for the Ketchikan-area neighborhoods in the 1980 census (Clover Pass, Herring Cove, Ketchikan East, Mountain Point, Alaska Route 7, Pennock Island and Saxman East), but have not been used since.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The remaining population was scattered throughout Alaska, both within organized boroughs and in the Unorganized Borough, in largely remote areas.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska is the coldest state in the United States.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The climate in the south and southeastern Alaska is a mid-latitude oceanic climate (Köppen climate classification: *Cfb*), and a subarctic oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfc*) in the northern parts, with cool summers and relatively mild winters.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] On an annual basis, the southeast is both the wettest and warmest part of Alaska with milder temperatures in the winter and high precipitation throughout the year.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Juneau averages over 50 in (130 cm) of precipitation a year, and Ketchikan averages over 150 in (380 cm).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] This is also the only region in Alaska in which the average daytime high temperature is above freezing during the winter months.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The climate of Anchorage and south central Alaska is mild by Alaskan standards due to the region's proximity to the seacoast.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] While the area gets less rain than southeast Alaska, it gets more snow, and days tend to be clearer.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] On average, Anchorage receives 16 in (41 cm) of precipitation a year, with around 75 in (190 cm) of snow, although there are areas in the south central which receive far more snow.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] It is a subarctic climate (Köppen: *Dfc*) due to its brief, cool summers.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The climate of western Alaska is determined in large part by the Bering Sea and the Gulf of Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] It is a subarctic oceanic climate in the southwest and a continental subarctic climate farther north.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The temperature is somewhat moderate considering how far north the area is.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] This region has a tremendous amount of variety in precipitation.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] An area stretching from the northern side of the Seward Peninsula to the Kobuk River valley (i.e., the region around Kotzebue Sound) is technically a desert, with portions receiving less than 10 in (25 cm) of precipitation annually.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] On the other extreme, some locations between Dillingham and Bethel average around 100 in (250 cm) of precipitation.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The climate of the interior of Alaska is subarctic and is a classic example of a continental subarctic climate, except in a few valleys where the climate approaches humid continental (Köppen: *Dfb*).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Some of the highest and lowest temperatures in Alaska occur around the area near Fairbanks.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Summers are warm, albeit generally short, and may have temperatures reaching into the 90s °F (the low-to-mid 30s °C).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In the long and very cold winters, the temperature can fall below −60 °F (−51 °C).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Precipitation is sparse in the Interior, often less than 10 in (25 cm) a year, but what precipitation falls in the winter tends to stay the entire winter.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The highest and lowest recorded temperatures in Alaska are both in the Interior.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The highest is 100 °F (38 °C) in Fort Yukon, which is just 8 mi or 13 km inside the arctic circle, on June 27, 1915, making Alaska tied with Hawaii as the state with the lowest high temperature in the United States.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The lowest official Alaska temperature is −80 °F (−62 °C) in Prospect Creek on January 23, 1971, one degree above the lowest temperature recorded in continental North America (in Snag, Yukon, Canada).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The climate in the extreme north of Alaska, north of the Brooks Range, is Arctic (Köppen: *ET*) with long, very cold winters and short, cool summers.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Even in July, the average low temperature in Utqiaġvik is 34 °F (1 °C).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Precipitation is light in this part of Alaska, with many places averaging less than 10 in (25 cm) per year, mostly as snow which stays on the ground almost the entire year.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The United States Census Bureau found in the 2020 United States census that the population of Alaska was 733,391 on April 1, 2020, a 3.3% increase since the 2010 United States census.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In the 2010 United States Census, Alaska had a population of 710,231, an increase of 13.3%, up from 626,932 at the 2000 U.S. census.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In 2020, Alaska ranked as the 48th largest state by population, ahead of only Vermont and Wyoming.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska is the least densely populated state, and one of the most sparsely populated areas in the world, at 1.2 inhabitants per square mile (0.46/km2).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The next state, Wyoming, has 5.8 inhabitants per square mile (2.2/km2).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska is by far the largest U.S. state by area, and the tenth wealthiest, per capita income.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] As of 2018 due to its population size, it is one of 14 U.S. states that still have only one telephone area code.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 2,320 homeless people in Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The 2019 American Community Survey estimated 60.2% of the population was white, 3.7% black or African American, 15.6% American Indian or Alaska Native, 6.5% Asian, 1.4% Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islander, 7.5% two or more races, and 7.3% Hispanic or Latin American.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] At the survey estimates, 7.8% of the total population was foreign-born from 2015 to 2019.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In 2015, 61.3% were white, 3.4% black or African American, 13.3% American Indian or Alaska Native, 6.2% Asian, 0.9% Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islander, 0.3% some other race, and 7.7% multiracial.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Hispanics and Latin Americans were 7% of the state population in 2015.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] From 2015 to 2019, the largest Hispanic and Latin American groups were Mexican Americans, Puerto Ricans, and Cuban Americans.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The largest Asian groups living in the state were Filipinos, Korean Americans, and Japanese and Chinese Americans.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In 2010, Alaska was 64.1% white, 14.8% American Indian and Alaska Native, 5.4% Asian, 3.3% black or African American, 1.0% Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islander, 1.6% from some other race, and 7.3% from two or more races in 2010.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Hispanics or Latin Americans made up 5.5% of the population in 2010.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] As of 2011, 50.7% of Alaska's population younger than one year of age belonged to minority groups (i.e., did not have two parents of white ancestry).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In 1960, the United States Census Bureau reported Alaska's population as 77.2% white, 3% black, and 18.8% American Indian and Alaska Native.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In 2018, the top countries of origin for Alaska's immigrants were the Philippines, Mexico, Canada, Thailand and South Korea.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In the 2011 American Community Survey, 83.4% of people over the age of five spoke only English at home.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] About 3.5% spoke Spanish at home, 2.2% spoke another Indo-European language, about 4.3% spoke an Asian language (including Tagalog), and about 5.3% spoke other languages at home.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In 2019, the American Community Survey determined 83.7% spoke only English, and 16.3% spoke another language other than English.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The most spoken European language after English was Spanish, spoken by approximately 4.0% of the state population.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Collectively, Asian and Pacific Islander languages were spoken by 5.6% of Alaskans.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Since 2010, 5.2% of Alaskans speak one of the state's 20 Indigenous languages, known locally as "Native languages".
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska is also known for a distinctive dialect of Russian, named Alaskan Russian.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The Alaska Native Language Center at the University of Alaska Fairbanks claims that at least twenty Alaska Native languages exist and there are also some languages with different dialects.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Most of Alaska's Native languages belong to either the Eskimo–Aleut or Na-Dene language families.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Some languages are thought to be isolates (e.g., Haida) or have not yet been classified (e.g., Tsimshianic).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In 2014, nearly all of Alaska's Native languages were classified as either threatened, shifting, moribund, nearly extinct, or dormant languages.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In October 2014, the governor of Alaska signed a bill declaring the state's 20 Indigenous languages to have official status.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] This bill gave them symbolic recognition as official languages, though they have not been adopted for official use within the government.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In May 2024, a bill replaced Tanana with Middle Tanana and Lower Tanana, added Cupʼig and Wetał.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Multiple surveys have ranked Alaska among the most irreligious states.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] ChangePoint in south Anchorage (left) and Anchorage Baptist Temple in east Anchorage are Alaska's largest churches in terms of attendance and membership.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In 2010, per the Association of Religion Data Archives (ARDA), about 34% of Alaska residents were members of religious congregations.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Of the religious population, roughly 4% were Mormon, 0.5% Jewish, 0.5% Muslim, 1% Buddhist, 0.2% Baháʼí, and 0.5% Hindu.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In 2010, the largest religious denominations in Alaska were the Catholic Church with 50,866 adherents; non-denominational Evangelicals with 38,070 adherents; The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints with 32,170 adherents; and the Southern Baptist Convention with 19,891 adherents.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska has been identified, along with Washington and Oregon in the Pacific Northwest, as being the least religious states in the United States, in terms of church membership.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The Pew Research Center in 2014 determined 62% of the adult population practiced Christianity.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Of the Christian denominations, Catholicism was the largest Christian group.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] When Protestant denominations were combined, Protestantism was the largest Christian tradition, with Evangelicalism being the largest movement within the Protestant group.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The unaffiliated population made up the largest non-Christian religious affiliation at 37%.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Atheists made up 5% of the population and the largest non-Christian religion was Buddhism.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In 2020, the Public Religion Research Institute (PRRI) determined 57% of adults were Christian.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] By 2022, Christianity increased to 77% of the population according to the PRRI.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Through the Association of Religion Data Archives in 2020, its Christian population was dominated by non/inter-denominational Protestantism as the single largest Christian cohort, with 73,930 adherents.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Roman Catholics were second with 40,280 members; throughout its Christian population, non-denominational Christians had an adherence rate of 100.81 per 1,000 residents, and Catholics 54.92 per 1,000 residents.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Per 2014's Pew study, religion was seen as very important to 41% of the population, although 29% considered it somewhat important.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In 2014, Pew determined roughly 55% believed in God with absolute certainty, and 24% believed fairly certainly.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Reflecting the separate 2020 ARDA study, the 2014 Pew study showed 30% attended religious services once a week, 34% once or twice a month, and 36% seldom/never.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In 1795, the first Russian Orthodox Church was established in Kodiak.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Intermarriage with Alaska Natives helped the Russian immigrants integrate into society.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] As a result, an increasing number of Russian Orthodox churches gradually became established within Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaska also has the largest Quaker population (by percentage) of any state.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In 2009, there were 6,000 Jews in Alaska, for whom observance of halakha may pose special problems.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Alaskan Hindus often share venues and celebrations with members of other Asian religious communities, including Sikhs and Jains.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In 2010, Alaskan Hindus established the Sri Ganesha Temple of Alaska, making it the first Hindu Temple in Alaska and the northernmost Hindu Temple in the world.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] There are an estimated 2,000–3,000 Hindus in Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The vast majority of Hindus live in Anchorage or Fairbanks.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Estimates for the number of Muslims in Alaska range from 2,000 to 5,000.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] In 2020, ARDA estimated there were 400 Muslims in the state.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] The Islamic Community Center of Anchorage began efforts in the late 1990s to construct a mosque in Anchorage.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] They broke ground on a building in south Anchorage in 2010 and were nearing completion in late 2014.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] When completed, the mosque was the first in the state and one of the northernmost mosques in the world.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] There is also a Baháʼí center, and there were 690 adherents in 2020.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p01] Additionally, there were 469 adherents of Hinduism and Yoga altogether in 2020, and a small number of Buddhists were present.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In October 2022, Alaska had a total employment of 316,900.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The number of employer establishments was 21,077.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] As of August 2025, the unemployment rate was 4.7%.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The state's historically lowest unemployment rate was recorded in August 2022 at 3.8%, and its highest in May 2020 at 11.7%.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Bureau of Economic Analysis, Alaska's gross state product was $75.011 billion in 2025.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Its per capita personal income was $80,175 in 2025.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] According to a 2013 study by Phoenix Marketing International, Alaska had the fifth-largest number of millionaires per capita in the United States, with a ratio of 6.75 percent.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The oil and gas industry dominates the Alaskan economy, with more than 80% of the state's revenues derived from petroleum extraction.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Alaska's main export product, excluding oil and natural gas, is seafood, primarily salmon, cod, pollock and crab.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Agriculture represents a minuscule fraction of the Alaskan economy.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Agricultural production is primarily for consumption within the state and includes nursery stock, dairy products, vegetables, and livestock.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Manufacturing is limited, with most foodstuffs and general goods imported from elsewhere.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Employment is primarily in government and industries such as natural resource extraction, shipping, and transportation.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Military bases are a significant component of the economy in Anchorage and the Fairbanks North Star and Kodiak Island boroughs.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In 2025, 99.1% of Alaska businesses are small businesses and employ 54.2% of the state's workforce.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Federal subsidies are also an important part of the economy, allowing the state to keep taxes low.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Its industrial outputs are crude petroleum, natural gas, coal, gold, precious metals, zinc and other mining, seafood processing, timber and wood products.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] There is also a growing service and tourism sector.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Tourists have contributed to the economy by supporting local lodging.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Alaska has vast energy resources, although its oil reserves have been largely depleted.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Major oil and gas reserves were found in the Alaska North Slope (ANS) and Cook Inlet basins, but according to the Energy Information Administration, by February 2014 Alaska had fallen to fourth place in the nation in crude oil production after Texas, North Dakota, and California.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Prudhoe Bay on Alaska's North Slope is still the second highest-yielding oil field in the United States, typically producing about 400,000 barrels per day (64,000 m3/d), although by early 2014 North Dakota's Bakken Formation was producing over 900,000 barrels per day (140,000 m3/d).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Trans-Alaska Pipeline can transport and pump up to 2.1 million barrels (330,000 m3) of crude oil per day, more than any other crude oil pipeline in the United States.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Substantial coal deposits are found in Alaska's bituminous, sub-bituminous, and lignite coal basins.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The United States Geological Survey estimates that there are 85.4 trillion cubic feet (2,420 km3) of undiscovered, technically recoverable gas from natural gas hydrates on the Alaskan North Slope.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Alaska also offers some of the highest hydroelectric power potential in the country from its numerous rivers.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Large swaths of the Alaskan coastline offer wind and geothermal energy potential as well.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Alaska's economy depends heavily on increasingly expensive diesel fuel for heating, transportation, electric power and light.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Although wind and hydroelectric power are abundant and underdeveloped, proposals for statewide energy systems were judged uneconomical (at the time of the report, 2001) due to low (less than 50¢/gal) fuel prices, long distances and low population.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Alaska Permanent Fund is a constitutionally authorized appropriation of oil revenues, established by voters in 1976 to manage a surplus in state petroleum revenues from oil, largely in anticipation of the then recently constructed Trans-Alaska Pipeline System.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The fund was originally proposed by Governor Keith Miller on the eve of the 1969 Prudhoe Bay lease sale, out of fear that the legislature would spend the entire proceeds of the sale (which amounted to $900 million) at once.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] It was later championed by Governor Jay Hammond and Kenai state representative Hugh Malone.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] It has served as an attractive political prospect ever since, diverting revenues which would normally be deposited into the general fund.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Alaska Constitution was written so as to discourage dedicating state funds for a particular purpose.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Permanent Fund has become the rare exception to this, mostly due to the political climate of distrust existing during the time of its creation.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] From its initial principal of $734,000, the fund has grown to $50 billion as a result of oil royalties and capital investment programs.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Most if not all the principal is invested conservatively outside Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] This has led to frequent calls by Alaskan politicians for the Fund to make investments within Alaska, though such a stance has never gained momentum.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Every year, the state legislature takes out 8% from the earnings, puts 3% back into the principal for inflation proofing, and the remaining 5% is distributed to all qualifying Alaskans.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Permanent Fund is often considered to be one of the leading examples of a basic income policy in the world.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The cost of goods in Alaska has long been higher than in the contiguous 48 states.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Federal government employees, particularly United States Postal Service (USPS) workers and active-duty military members, receive a Cost of Living Allowance usually set at 25% of base pay because, while the cost of living has gone down, it is still one of the highest in the country.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Rural Alaska suffers from severely high prices for food and consumer goods compared to the rest of the country, due to the relatively limited transportation infrastructure.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Due to the northern climate and short growing season, relatively little farming occurs in Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Most farms are in either the Matanuska Valley, about 40 miles (64 km) northeast of Anchorage, or on the Kenai Peninsula, about 60 miles (97 km) southwest of Anchorage.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The short 100-day growing season limits the crops that can be grown, but the long sunny summer days make for productive growing seasons.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The primary crops are potatoes, carrots, lettuce, and cabbage.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Tanana Valley is another notable agricultural locus, especially the Delta Junction area, about 100 miles (160 km) southeast of Fairbanks, with a sizable concentration of farms growing agronomic crops; these farms mostly lie north and east of Fort Greely.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] This area was largely set aside and developed under a state program spearheaded by Hammond during his second term as governor.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Delta-area crops consist predominantly of barley and hay.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] West of Fairbanks lies another concentration of small farms catering to restaurants, the hotel and tourist industry, and community-supported agriculture.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Alaskan agriculture has experienced a surge in growth of market gardeners, small farms and farmers' markets in recent years, with the highest percentage increase (46%) in the nation in growth in farmers' markets in 2011, compared to 17% nationwide.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The peony industry has also taken off, as the growing season allows farmers to harvest during a gap in supply elsewhere in the world, thereby filling a niche in the flower market.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Alaska, with no counties, lacks county fairs.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Instead, a small assortment of state and local fairs (with the Alaska State Fair in Palmer the largest), are held mostly in the late summer.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The fairs are mostly located in communities with historic or current agricultural activity, and feature local farmers exhibiting produce in addition to more high-profile commercial activities such as carnival rides, concerts and food.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] "Alaska Grown" is used as an agricultural slogan.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Alaska has an abundance of seafood, with the primary fisheries in the Bering Sea and the North Pacific.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Seafood is one of the few food items that is often cheaper within the state than outside it.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Many Alaskans take advantage of salmon seasons to harvest portions of their household diet while fishing for subsistence, as well as sport.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] This includes fish taken by hook, net or wheel.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Hunting for subsistence, primarily caribou, moose, and Dall sheep is still common in the state, particularly in remote Bush communities.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] An example of a traditional native food is Akutaq, the Eskimo ice cream, which can consist of reindeer fat, seal oil, dried fish meat and local berries.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Alaska's reindeer herding is concentrated on Seward Peninsula, where wild caribou can be prevented from mingling and migrating with the domesticated reindeer.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Most food in Alaska is transported into the state from "Outside" (the other 49 U.S. states), and shipping costs make food in the cities relatively expensive.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In rural areas, subsistence hunting and gathering is an essential activity because imported food is prohibitively expensive.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Although most small towns and villages in Alaska lie along the coastline, the cost of importing food to remote villages can be high because of the terrain and difficult road conditions, which change dramatically due to varying climate and precipitation changes.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Transport costs can reach 50¢ per pound ($1.10/kg) or higher in some remote areas during times of inclement weather or rough terrain conditions, if these locations can be reached at all.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The cost of delivering a gallon (3.8 L) of milk is about $3.50 in many villages where per capita income can be $20,000 or less.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Fuel cost per gallon is routinely twenty to thirty cents higher than the contiguous United States average, with only Hawaii having higher prices.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Some of Alaska's popular annual events are the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race from Anchorage to Nome, World Ice Art Championships in Fairbanks, the Blueberry Festival and Alaska Hummingbird Festival in Ketchikan, the Sitka Whale Fest, and the Stikine River Garnet Fest in Wrangell.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Stikine River attracts the largest springtime concentration of American bald eagles in the world.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Alaska Native Heritage Center celebrates the rich heritage of Alaska's 11 cultural groups.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Their purpose is to encourage cross-cultural exchanges among all people and enhance self-esteem among Native people.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Alaska Native Arts Foundation promotes and markets Native art from all regions and cultures in the State, using the internet.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Influences on music in Alaska include the traditional music of Alaska Natives as well as folk music brought by later immigrants from Russia and Europe.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Prominent musicians from Alaska include singer Jewel, traditional Aleut flautist Mary Youngblood, folk singer-songwriter Libby Roderick, Christian music singer-songwriter Lincoln Brewster, metal/post hardcore band 36 Crazyfists and the groups Pamyua and Portugal.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] There are many established music festivals in Alaska, including the Alaska Folk Festival, the Fairbanks Summer Arts Festival, the Anchorage Folk Festival, the Athabascan Old-Time Fiddling Festival, the Sitka Jazz Festival, the Sitka Summer Music Festival, and the Anchorage Chamber Music Festival.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The most prominent orchestra in Alaska is the Anchorage Symphony Orchestra, though the Fairbanks Symphony Orchestra and Juneau Symphony are also notable.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Anchorage Opera is currently the state's only professional opera company, though there are several volunteer and semi-professional organizations in the state as well.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The official state song of Alaska is "Alaska's Flag", which was adopted in 1955; it celebrates the flag of Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The 1983 Disney movie *Never Cry Wolf* was at least partially shot in Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The 1991 film *White Fang*, based on Jack London's 1906 novel and starring Ethan Hawke, was filmed in and around Haines.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Steven Seagal's 1994 *On Deadly Ground*, starring Michael Caine, was filmed in part at the Worthington Glacier near Valdez.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Many reality television shows are filmed in Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In 2011, the *Anchorage Daily News* found ten set in the state.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The following is a list of sporting venues, events, and teams based in Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Alaska State Troopers are Alaska's statewide police force.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] They have a long and storied history, but were not an official organization until 1941.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Before the force was officially organized, law enforcement in Alaska was handled by various federal agencies.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Larger towns usually have their own local police and some villages rely on "Public Safety Officers" who have police training but do not carry firearms.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In much of the state, the troopers serve as the only police force available.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In addition to enforcing traffic and criminal law, wildlife Troopers enforce hunting and fishing regulations.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Due to the varied terrain and wide scope of the Troopers' duties, they employ a wide variety of land, air, and water patrol vehicles.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Many rural communities in Alaska are considered "dry", having outlawed the importation of alcoholic beverages.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Suicide rates for rural residents are higher than urban rates.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Domestic abuse and other violent crimes are at high levels in Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] This is in part linked to alcohol abuse.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Alaska has the highest rate of sexual assault in the nation, especially in rural areas.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The average age of sexually assaulted victims is 16 years old.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In four out of five cases, the suspects were relatives, friends, or acquaintances.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] As of 2022, CVS Health and Premera account for 47% and 46% of private health insurance, respectively.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Premera and Moda Health offer insurance on the federally-run Affordable Care Exchange.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Providence Alaska Medical Center in Anchorage is the largest hospital in the state as of 2021; Anchorage also hosts Alaska Regional Hospital and Alaska Native Medical Center.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Alaska's other major cities such as Fairbanks and Juneau also have local hospitals.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In Southeast Alaska, Southeast Alaska Regional Health Consortium, runs healthcare facilities across 27 communities as of 2022, including hospitals in Sitka and Wrangell; although it originally served Native Americans only, it has expanded access and combined with other local facilities over time.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Alaska Department of Education and Early Development administers many school districts in Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In addition, the state operates a boarding school, Mt.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Edgecumbe High School in Sitka, and provides partial funding for other boarding schools, including Nenana Student Living Center in Nenana and The Galena Interior Learning Academy in Galena.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] There are more than a dozen colleges and universities in Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Accredited universities in Alaska include the University of Alaska Anchorage, University of Alaska Fairbanks, University of Alaska Southeast, and Alaska Pacific University.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Alaska is the only state that has no collegiate athletic programs that are members of NCAA Division I, although both Alaska-Fairbanks and Alaska-Anchorage maintain single sport membership in Division I for men's ice hockey.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Alaska Department of Labor and Workforce Development operates AVTEC, Alaska's Institute of Technology.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Campuses in Seward and Anchorage offer one-week to 11-month training programs in areas as diverse as Information Technology, Welding, Nursing, and Mechanics.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Alaska has had a problem with a "brain drain".
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Many of its young people, including most of the highest academic achievers, leave the state after high school graduation and do not return.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] As of 2013 Alaska did not have a law school or medical school.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The University of Alaska has attempted to combat this by offering partial four-year scholarships to the top 10% of Alaska high school graduates, via the Alaska Scholars Program.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Beginning in 1998, schools in rural Alaska must have at least ten students to retain funding from the state, and campuses not meeting the number close.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] This was due to the loss in oil revenues that previously propped up smaller rural schools.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In 2015, there was a proposal to raise that minimum to 25, but legislators in the state largely did not agree.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Alaska has few road connections compared to the rest of the U.S.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The state's road system, covering a relatively small area of the state, linking the central population centers and the Alaska Highway, the principal route out of the state through Canada.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The state capital, Juneau, is not accessible by road, with access only by ferry or flight; this has spurred debate over decades about moving the capital to a city on the road system, or building a road connection from Haines.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The western part of Alaska has no road system connecting the communities with the rest of Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Interstate Highways in Alaska consists of a total of 1,082 miles (1,741 km).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] These are mostly not built to Interstate Highway standards and their status as such is largely notional.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] A unique feature of the Alaska Highway system is the Anton Anderson Memorial Tunnel, an active Alaska Railroad tunnel that provides a paved roadway link with the isolated community of Whittier on Prince William Sound to the Seward Highway about 50 miles (80 km) southeast of Anchorage at Portage.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] At 2.5 miles (4.0 km), the tunnel was the longest road tunnel in North America until 2007.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The tunnel is the longest combination road and rail tunnel in North America.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Southwest Alaska is largely coastal, sparsely populated, and unconnected to the road system.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Access to most communities in Southwest Alaska is primarily by air taxi, although larger towns like Kodiak, Bethel, King Salmon, Dillingham, and Dutch Harbor are accessible by scheduled air service.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Some coastal communities can be reached via the Alaska Marine Highway ferry.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Built around 1915, the Alaska Railroad (ARR) played a key role in the development of Alaska through the 20th century.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] It links shipping lanes on the North Pacific with Interior Alaska with tracks that run from Seward by way of South Central Alaska, passing through Anchorage, Eklutna, Wasilla, Talkeetna, Denali, and Fairbanks, with spurs to Whittier, Palmer and North Pole.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The cities, towns, villages, and region served by ARR tracks are known statewide as "The Railbelt".
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In recent years, the ever-improving paved highway system began to eclipse the railroad's importance in Alaska's economy.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The railroad played a vital role in Alaska's development, moving freight into Alaska while transporting natural resources southward, such as coal from the Usibelli coal mine near Healy to Seward and gravel from the Matanuska Valley to Anchorage.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] It is well known for its summertime tour passenger service.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Alaska Railroad was one of the last railroads in North America to use cabooses in regular service and still uses them on some gravel trains.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] It continues to offer one of the last flag stop routes in the country.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] A stretch of about 60 miles (100 km) of track along an area north of Talkeetna remains inaccessible by road; the railroad provides the only transportation to rural homes and cabins in the area.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Until construction of the Parks Highway in the 1970s, the railroad provided the only land access to most of the region along its entire route.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In northern Southeast Alaska, the White Pass and Yukon Route also partly runs through the state from Skagway northwards into Canada (British Columbia and Yukon Territory), crossing the border at White Pass Summit.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] This line is now mainly used by tourists, often arriving by cruise liner at Skagway.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] It was featured in the 1983 BBC television series *Great Little Railways*.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] These two railroads are connected neither to each other nor any other railroad.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The nearest link to the North American railway network is the northwest terminus of the Canadian National Railway at Prince Rupert, British Columbia, several hundred miles to the southeast.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Congress authorized $6 million to study the feasibility of a rail link between Alaska, Canada, and the lower 48.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] As of 2021 the Alaska-Alberta Railway Development Corporation is in receivership.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Some private companies provides car float service between Whittier and Seattle.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Many cities, towns, and villages in Alaska don't have road or highway access.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The only modes of access involve travel by air, river, or the sea.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Alaska's well-developed state-owned ferry system, known as the Alaska Marine Highway, serves the cities of southeast, the Gulf Coast and the Alaska Peninsula.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The ferries transport vehicles and passengers.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The system also operates a ferry service from Bellingham, Washington and Prince Rupert, British Columbia, in Canada through the Inside Passage to Skagway.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Inter-Island Ferry Authority also serves as an important marine link for many communities in the Prince of Wales Island region of Southeast and works in concert with the Alaska Marine Highway.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In recent years, cruise lines have created a summertime tourism market, mainly connecting the Pacific Northwest to Southeast Alaska and, to a lesser degree, towns along Alaska's gulf coast.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The population of Ketchikan for example fluctuates dramatically on many days—up to four large cruise ships can dock there at the same time.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Cities not served by road, sea, or river can be reached only by air, foot, dogsled, or snowmachine, accounting for Alaska's extremely well developed bush air services—an Alaskan novelty.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Anchorage, and to a lesser extent Fairbanks, is served by many major airlines.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Because of limited highway access, air travel remains the most efficient form of transportation in and out of the state.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Anchorage recently completed extensive remodeling and construction at Ted Stevens Anchorage International Airport to help accommodate the upsurge in tourism.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In 2012–2013, Alaska received almost two million visitors.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Making regular flights to most villages and towns within the state commercially viable is difficult, so they are heavily subsidized by the federal government through the Essential Air Service program.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The bulk of remaining commercial flight offerings come from small regional commuter airlines such as Ravn Alaska, PenAir, and Frontier Flying Service.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The smallest towns and villages must rely on scheduled or chartered bush flying services using general aviation aircraft such as the Cessna Caravan, the most popular aircraft in use in the state.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Much of this service can be attributed to the Alaska bypass mail program which subsidizes bulk mail delivery to Alaskan rural communities.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The program requires 70% of that subsidy to go to carriers who offer passenger service to the communities.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Many communities have small air taxi services.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] These operations originated from the demand for customized transport to remote areas.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Perhaps the most quintessentially Alaskan plane is the bush seaplane.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The world's busiest seaplane base is Lake Hood, located next to Ted Stevens Anchorage International Airport, where flights bound for remote villages without an airstrip carry passengers, cargo, and many items from stores and warehouse clubs.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In 2006, Alaska had the highest number of pilots per capita of any U.S. state.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In Alaska there are 8,795 active pilot certificates as of 2020.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Another Alaskan transportation method is the dogsled.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In modern times, that is, any time after the mid- to late‑1920s, dog mushing is more of a sport than a true means of transportation.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Races are held around the state, but the best known is the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race, a 1,150-mile (1,850 km) trail from Anchorage to Nome, although the distance varies from year to year, the official distance is set at 1,049 miles or 1,688 km.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The race commemorates the famous 1925 serum run to Nome in which mushers and dogs like Togo and Balto took much-needed medicine to the diphtheria-stricken community of Nome when all other means of transportation had failed.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Mushers from all over the world come to Anchorage each March to compete for cash, prizes, and prestige.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The "Serum Run" is another sled dog race that more accurately follows the route of the famous 1925 relay, leaving from the community of Nenana, southwest of Fairbanks, to Nome.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In areas not served by road or rail, primary transportation in summer is by fourwheeler and in winter by snowmachine.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Alaska's internet and other data transport systems are provided largely through the two major telecommunications companies: GCI and Alaska Communications.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] GCI owns and operates what it calls the Alaska United Fiber Optic system.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] As of late 2011, Alaska Communications had two fiber optic paths to the lower 48 and two more across Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In January 2011, it was reported that a $1 billion project to connect Asia and rural Alaska was being planned, aided in part by $350 million in stimulus from the federal government.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The state of Alaska employs approximately 16,000 people statewide.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Alaska State Legislature consists of a 40-member House of Representatives and a 20-member Senate.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Senators serve four-year terms and House members two.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The governor of Alaska serves four-year terms.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The lieutenant governor runs separately from the governor in the primaries, but during the general election, the nominee for governor and nominee for lieutenant governor run together on the same ticket.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Alaska's court system has four levels: the Alaska Supreme Court, the Alaska Court of Appeals, the Superior Court and the district courts.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The superior and district courts are trial courts.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Superior courts are courts of general jurisdiction, while district courts hear only certain types of cases, including misdemeanor criminal cases and civil cases valued up to $100,000.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Supreme Court and the Court of Appeals are appellate courts.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Court of Appeals is required to hear appeals from certain lower-court decisions, including those regarding criminal prosecutions, juvenile delinquency, and habeas corpus.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Supreme Court hears civil appeals and may in its discretion hear criminal appeals.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Although in its early years of statehood Alaska was a Democratic state, since the early 1970s it has been characterized as Republican-leaning.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Local political communities have often worked on issues related to land use development, fishing, tourism, and individual rights.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Alaska Natives, while organized in and around their communities, have been active within the Native corporations.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] These have been given ownership over large tracts of land, which require stewardship.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Alaska was formerly the only state in which possession of one ounce or less of marijuana in one's home was completely legal under state law, though the federal law remains in force.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The state has an independence movement favoring a vote on secession from the United States, with the Alaskan Independence Party.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Six Republicans and four Democrats have served as governor of Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Republican governor Wally Hickel was elected to the office for a second term in 1990 after leaving the Republican party and briefly joining the Alaskan Independence Party ticket just long enough to be reelected.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] He rejoined the Republican party in 1994.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Alaska's voter initiative making marijuana legal took effect in February 2015, placing Alaska alongside Colorado and Washington, as well as Washington D.C., as the first three U.S. states where recreational marijuana is legal.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The law means people over 21 can consume small amounts of cannabis.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The first legal marijuana store opened in Valdez in October 2016.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] To finance state government operations, Alaska depends primarily on petroleum revenues and federal subsidies.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] This allows it to have the lowest individual tax burden in the United States.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] It is one of five states with no sales tax, one of seven states with no individual income tax, and—along with New Hampshire—one of two that has neither.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Department of Revenue Tax Division reports regularly on the state's revenue sources.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The department issues an annual summary of its operations, including new state laws that directly affect the tax division.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In 2014, the Tax Foundation ranked Alaska as having the fourth most "business friendly" tax policy, behind only Wyoming, South Dakota, and Nevada.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] 89 municipalities collect a local sales tax, from 1.0 to 7.5%, typically 3–5%.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Other local taxes levied include raw fish taxes, hotel, motel, and bed-and-breakfast 'bed' taxes, severance taxes, liquor and tobacco taxes, gaming (pull tabs) taxes, tire taxes and fuel transfer taxes.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] A part of the revenue collected from certain state taxes and license fees, such as petroleum, aviation motor fuel, telephone cooperative, is shared with municipalities in Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The fall in oil prices after the fracking boom in the early 2010s has decimated Alaska's state treasury, which has historically received about 85 percent of its revenue from taxes and fees imposed on oil and gas companies.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The state government has had to drastically reduce its budget, and has brought its budget shortfall from over $2 billion in 2016 to under $500 million by 2018.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In 2020, Alaska's state government budget was $4.8 billion, while projected government revenues were only $4.5 billion.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Alaska regularly supports Republicans in presidential elections and has done so since statehood.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Republicans have won the state's electoral college votes in all but one election that it has participated in (1964).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] No state has voted for a Democratic presidential candidate fewer times.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Alaska was carried by Democratic nominee Lyndon B.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Johnson during his landslide election in 1964, while the 1960 and 1968 elections were close.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Since 1972, Republicans have carried the state by large margins.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In 2008, Republican John McCain defeated Democrat Barack Obama in Alaska, 59.49% to 37.83%.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] McCain's running mate was Sarah Palin, the state's governor and the first Alaskan on a major party ticket.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Obama lost Alaska again in 2012, but he captured 40% of the state's vote in that election, making him the first Democrat to do so since 1968.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In 2020, Joe Biden received 42.77% of the vote for president, marking the high point for a Democratic presidential candidate since Johnson's 1964 victory.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Alaska Bush, central Juneau, midtown and downtown Anchorage, and the areas surrounding the University of Alaska Fairbanks campus and Ester have been strongholds of the Democratic Party.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The Matanuska-Susitna Borough, the Kenai Peninsula, the majority of Fairbanks (including North Pole and the military base), and South Anchorage typically have the strongest Republican showing.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Alaska has a history of primary defeats for incumbent U.S.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Senators, including Ernest Gruening, Mike Gravel, and Lisa Murkowski.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] However, Murkowski won re-election with a write-in campaign.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Despite this, Alaska has also seen long-serving members of Congress, such as Ted Stevens, who served as a U.S.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Senator for 40 years, and Don Young, who held Alaska's sole U.S.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] House seat for 49 years, from 1973 to 2022.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] In the 2020 election cycle, Alaskan voters approved Ballot Measure 2.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The measure passed by a margin of 1.1%, or about 4,000 votes.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The measure requires campaigns to disclose the original source and any intermediaries for campaign contributions over $2,000.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The measure also establishes non-partisan primaries, sometimes called jungle primaries, for statewide elections (like in Washington state and California) and ranked-choice voting, like in Maine.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] Measure 2 makes Alaska the third state with nonpartisan primaries for all statewide races, the second state with ranked choice voting, and the only state with both.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] The 2022 special election to fill Alaska's only U.S.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] House seat, left vacant by the death of Don Young, was won by Mary Peltola.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] She became the first Democrat to win the House seat since 1972 and the first Alaskan Native elected to the United States Congress in history.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-p02] After winning a full term in the 2022 general election, Peltola lost reelection in 2024 to Republican Nick Begich III.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] The **Alaska Peninsula** (also called the **Aleut Peninsula** or the **Aleutian Peninsula**, Aleut: *Alaxsxix̂*; Sugpiaq: *Aluuwiq*, *Al'uwiq*) is a peninsula extending about 497 mi (800 km) to the southwest from the mainland of Alaska and ending in the Aleutian Islands.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] The peninsula separates the Pacific Ocean from Bristol Bay, an arm of the Bering Sea.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] In literature (especially Russian), the term *Alaska Peninsula* was used to denote the entire north-western protrusion of the North American continent, or all of what is now the state of Alaska, exclusive of its panhandle and islands.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] The Lake and Peninsula borough, the Alaskan equivalent of a county, is named after the peninsula.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] The Alaska/Aleutian Peninsula is also grouped into Southwest Alaska.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] The other large peninsulas in Alaska include the Kenai Peninsula and the Seward Peninsula.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] The base of the Alaska Peninsula extends outward from the end of the Alaska Range.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] The Aleutian Range is a very active volcanic mountain range which runs along the entire length of the peninsula.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] Within it lie Wildlife Refuges, including the Katmai National Park and Preserve, the Aniakchak National Monument and Preserve and the Becharof National Wildlife Refuge, the Alaska Peninsula National Wildlife Refuge, and the Izembek National Wildlife Refuge.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] The most active volcano along the volcanic mountain range is Pavlof Volcano which is more than 8,251 feet (2,515 meters)(see also: Aleutian Arc).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] The northern and southern shores are likewise quite different.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] The northern Bristol Bay coastal side is generally turbid and muddy, experiences tidal extremes, and is relatively shallow; the Pacific side, which is also known as the "ring of fire", has relatively small tidal activity and the water is deep and clear.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] The peninsula is organized as a part of four adjacent boroughs; the Aleutians East Borough, Bristol Bay Borough, Kodiak Island Borough, and Lake and Peninsula Borough.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] The Lake and Peninsula Borough includes most of the peninsula's territory.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] Average annual precipitation ranges from 24–65 in (610–1,650 mm).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] Coastal areas are subject to intense storms, wind, and rain.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] Winter temperatures average between 12 and 34 °F (−11 and 1 °C), and in summer between 43 and 59 °F (6 and 15 °C).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] Frosts can occur any day of the year at higher elevations.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] The climate can be compared to that of parts of Scotland, the Aleutian Islands, Iceland, and Tierra del Fuego.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] The Alaska Peninsula is home to some of the largest populations of native and undisturbed wildlife in the United States.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] Besides the famous McNeil River and Katmai Alaskan brown bear populations, large herds of caribou, moose, wolves, waterfowl, and willow ptarmigan inhabit the area.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] The bears of the peninsula and Bristol Bay are so numerous because they feed on the world's largest sockeye salmon (*Oncorhynchus nerka*) runs, which occur here in large part because the many large lakes of the peninsula are an important element in their lifecycle.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] These salmon, after returning from their brief time at sea, swim into the lakes and their contributing streams to spawn.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] Their offspring, or *fry*, overwinter in the deep and food-abundant depths of these lakes until their migration to the sea in one or two years.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] Exceptionally large seabird colonies exist along the coast.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] Additionally, there are large populations of sea mammals in the North Pacific Ocean between the Alaska Peninsula and Kamchatka.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] This includes harbor seals, ringed seals, northern fur seals, whales, porpoises, sea otters and sea lions.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] The rugged southern half of the peninsula, and also the Kodiak Archipelago which lie off the south coast of the peninsula and are home to even more bears, constitute the Alaska Peninsula montane taiga ecoregion and contain a number of protected areas such as Katmai National Park.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] Vegetation on the peninsula consists mostly of shrub-lands, grassy meadows, or wet tundra.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] Besides the communities on the coast (*see: Bristol Bay*), the Alaska Peninsula also is home to several well-known villages: Cold Bay, King Cove, Perryville, Chignik, Chignik Lake, Chignik Lagoon, and Port Moller.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-peninsula] Each is primarily inhabited by Alaska Natives and each, likewise, is mostly dependent on the fishing industry for sustenance.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] The **Alaska Range** is a relatively narrow, 600-mile-long (970-kilometer) mountain range in the southcentral region of the U.S. state of Alaska, from Lake Clark at its southwest end to the White River in Canada's Yukon Territory in the southeast.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] Denali, the highest mountain in North America, is in the Alaska Range.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] The range is part of the American Cordillera.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] The Alaska Range is one of the highest mountain ranges in the world, after the Himalayas and the Andes.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] The range forms a generally east–west arc with its northernmost part in the center, and from there trending southwest towards the Alaska Peninsula and the Aleutian Islands, and trending southeast into British Columbia and the Pacific Coast Ranges.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] The mountains act as a high barrier to the flow of moist air from the Gulf of Alaska northwards, and thus have some of the harshest weather in the world.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] The heavy snowfall also contributes to a number of large glaciers, including the Cantwell, Castner, Black Rapids, Susitna, Yanert, Muldrow, Eldridge, Ruth, Tokositna, and Kahiltna Glaciers.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] Four major rivers cross the Alaska Range, including the Delta and Nenana Rivers in the center of the range and the Nabesna and Chisana Rivers to the east.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] The range is part of the Pacific Ring of Fire, and the Denali Fault that runs along its southern edge is responsible for many major earthquakes.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] Mount Spurr is a stratovolcano located at the northeastern end of the Aleutian Volcanic Arc which has two vents, the summit and nearby Crater Peak.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] Parts of the Alaska Range are protected within Wrangell-St.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] Elias National Park and Preserve, Denali National Park and Preserve, and Lake Clark National Park and Preserve.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] Several highways cross through the passes of the range: the George Parks Highway from Anchorage to Fairbanks via Windy Pass, the Richardson Highway from Valdez to Fairbanks via Isabel Pass, and the Tok Cut-Off from Gulkana Junction to Tok, Alaska via Mentasta Pass.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] The Alaska Pipeline parallels the Richardson Highway.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] A part of the Alaska Highway is situated on the northern slopes of the eastern section of the range.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] The name "Alaskan Range" appears to have been first applied to these mountains in 1869 by naturalist W.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] The name eventually became "Alaska Range" through local use.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] In 1849 Constantin Grewingk applied the name "Tschigmit" to this mountain range.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] A map made by the United States General Land Office in 1869 calls the southwestern part of the Alaska Range the "Chigmit Mountains" and the northeastern part the "Beaver Mountains".
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] However, the Chigmit Mountains are now considered part of the Aleutian Range.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] Starting in the mid-1880s to early 1900s, early non-native explorers traversed various sections of the Alaska Range.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] The first recorded expedition was in the Eastern Alaska Range led by H.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] His team went from Suslota Lake to Tetlin Lake and unto the Tanana River via Miles Pass.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] He noted that it would be possible to build a road from Prince William Sound to the Yukon River.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] Six years later, Frederick Schwatka and Charles W.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] Hayes crossed the extreme eastern end of the range via the White River and into the Copper River basin through Skolai Pass in what is now called Saint Elias Mountains.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] Glenn traversed Isabel Pass and were within 15–20 miles of the Tanana River before turning around.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alaska-range] Separately, that same year, Robert Muldrow and George Homans Eldridge crossed Broad Pass then Windy Pass into the Nenana River valley.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] With a few exceptions, alders are deciduous, and the leaves are alternate, simple, and serrated.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] The flowers are catkins with elongate male catkins on the same plant as shorter female catkins, often before leaves appear; they are mainly wind-pollinated, but also visited by bees to a small extent.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] These trees differ from the birches (*Betula*, another genus in the family) in that the female catkins are woody and do not disintegrate at maturity, opening to release the seeds in a similar manner to many conifer cones.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] The largest species are red alder (*A. rubra*) on the west coast of North America, and black alder (*A. glutinosa*), native to most of Europe and widely introduced elsewhere, both reaching over 30 metres (100 ft).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] By contrast, the widespread *Alnus alnobetula* (green alder) is rarely more than a 5 m-tall (16 ft) shrub.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] The oldest fossil pollen that can be identified as *Alnus* is from northern Bohemia, dating to the late Paleocene, around 58 million years ago.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] The common name *alder* evolved from the Old English word *alor*, which in turn is derived from Proto-Germanic root *aliso*.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] The generic name *Alnus* is the equivalent Latin name, from whence French *aulne* and Spanish *Alamo* (Spanish term for "poplar").
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Alders are commonly found near streams, rivers, and wetlands.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Sometimes where the prevalence of alders is particularly prominent these are called alder carrs.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] In the Pacific Northwest of North America, the white alder (*Alnus rhombifolia*) unlike other northwest alders, has an affinity for warm, dry climates, where it grows along watercourses, such as along the lower Columbia River east of the Cascades and the Snake River, including Hells Canyon.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Alder leaves and sometimes catkins are used as food by numerous butterflies and moths.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Alder is particularly noted for its important symbiotic relationship with *Frankia alni*, an actinomycete, filamentous, nitrogen-fixing bacterium.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] This bacterium is found in root nodules, which may be as large as a human fist, with many small lobes, and light brown in colour.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] The bacterium absorbs nitrogen from the air and makes it available to the tree.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Alder, in turn, provides the bacterium with sugars, which it produces through photosynthesis.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] As a result of this mutually beneficial relationship, alder improves the fertility of the soil where it grows, and as a pioneer species, it helps provide additional nitrogen for the successional species to follow.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Because of its abundance, red alder delivers large amounts of nitrogen to enrich forest soils.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Red alder stands have been found to supply between 130 and 320 kilograms per hectare (120 and 290 pounds per acre) of nitrogen annually to the soil.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] From Alaska to Oregon, *Alnus viridis* subsp.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] *sinuata* (*A. sinuata*, Sitka alder or slide alder), characteristically pioneer fresh, gravelly sites at the foot of retreating glaciers.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Studies show that Sitka alder, a more shrubby variety of alder, adds nitrogen to the soil at an average rate of 60 kg/ha (54 lb/acre) per year, helping convert the sterile glacial terrain to soil capable of supporting a conifer forest.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Alders are common among the first species to colonize disturbed areas from floods, windstorms, fires, landslides, etc.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Alder groves often serve as natural firebreaks since these broad-leaved trees are much less flammable than conifers.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Their foliage and leaf litter does not carry a fire well, and their thin bark is sufficiently resistant to protect them from light surface fires.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] In addition, the light weight of alder seeds – numbering 1.5 million per kilogram or 680,000 per pound – allows for easy dispersal by the wind.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Although it outgrows coastal Douglas-fir for the first 25 years, it is very shade intolerant and seldom lives more than 100 years.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Red alder is the Pacific Northwest's largest alder and the most plentiful and commercially important broad-leaved tree in the coastal Northwest.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Groves of red alder 25 to 50 centimetres (10 to 20 in) in diameter intermingle with young Douglas-fir forests west of the Cascades, attaining a maximum height of 30 to 33 m (100 to 110 ft) in about sixty years, and then are afflicted by heart rot.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Alders largely help create conditions favorable for giant conifers that replace them.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Alder roots are parasitized by northern groundcone.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] The catkins of some alder species have a degree of edibility, and may be rich in protein.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Reported to have a bitter and unpleasant taste, they are more useful for survival purposes.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] The wood of certain alder species is often used to smoke various food items such as coffee, salmon, and other seafood.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Alder is notably stable when immersed, and has been used for millennia as a material for pilings for piers and wharves.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Most of the pilings that form the foundation of Venice were made from alder trees.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Alder bark contains the anti-inflammatory salicin, which is metabolized into salicylic acid in the body.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Some Native American cultures use red alder bark (*Alnus rubra*) to treat poison oak, insect bites, and skin irritations.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Blackfeet Indians have traditionally used an infusion made from the bark of red alder to treat lymphatic disorders and tuberculosis.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Recent clinical studies have verified that red alder contains betulin and lupeol, compounds shown to be effective against a variety of tumors.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] The inner bark of the alder, as well as red osier dogwood, or chokecherry, is used by some Indigenous peoples of the Americas in smoking mixtures, known as *kinnikinnick*, to improve the taste of the bearberry leaf.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Alder is illustrated in the coat of arms for the Austrian town of Grossarl.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Electric guitars, most notably those manufactured by the Fender Musical Instruments Corporation, have been built with alder bodies since the 1950s.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Alder is appreciated for its tone that is claimed to be tight and evenly balanced, especially when compared to mahogany, and has been adopted by many electric guitar manufacturers.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] It usually is finished in opaque lacquer (nitrocellulose, polyurethane, or polyester), as it does not have a prominent grain.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] As a hardwood, alder is used in making furniture, cabinets, and other woodworking products.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] In these applications, its aforementioned lack of prominent grain means that it is often veneered, either by stained light woods such as oak, ash, or figured maple, or by darker woods such as teak or walnut.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Alder bark and wood (like oak and sweet chestnut) contain tannin and are traditionally used to tan leather.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] A red dye can also be extracted from the outer bark, and a yellow dye from the inner bark.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alder] Ermanno Olmi's movie *The Tree of Wooden Clogs* (*L' Albero Degli Zoccoli*, 1978) refers in its title to alder, typically used to make clogs as in this movie's plot.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] The high elevation causes an adverse climate, which is too cold and windy to support tree growth.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Alpine tundra transitions to sub-alpine forests below the tree line; stunted forests occurring at the forest-tundra ecotone are known as *krummholz*.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] With increasing elevation it ends at the snow line where snow and ice persist through summer.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Alpine tundra occurs in mountains worldwide.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] The flora of the alpine tundra is characterized by dwarf shrubs close to the ground.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] The cold climate of the alpine tundra is caused by adiabatic cooling of air, and is similar to polar climate.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Alpine tundra occurs at high enough altitude at any latitude.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Portions of montane grasslands and shrublands ecoregions worldwide include alpine tundra.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Alpine tundra occupies high-mountain summits, slopes, and ridges above timberline.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Aspect plays a role as well; the treeline often occurs at higher elevations on warmer equator-facing slopes.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Because the alpine zone is present only on mountains, much of the landscape is rugged and broken, with rocky, snowcapped peaks, cliffs, and talus slopes, but also contains areas of gently rolling to almost flat topography.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Averaging over many locations and local microclimates, the treeline rises 75 meters (245 ft) when moving 1 degree south from 70 to 50°N, and 130 meters (430 ft) per degree from 50 to 30°N.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Alpine climate is the average weather (climate) for the alpine tundra.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] The climate becomes colder when reaching higher elevations—this characteristic is described by the lapse rate of air: air tends to get colder as it rises, since it expands.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] The dry adiabatic lapse rate is 10 °C per km (5.5 °F per 1000 ft) of elevation or altitude.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Therefore, moving up 100 meters (330 ft) on a mountain is roughly equivalent to moving 80 kilometers (45 miles or 0.75° of latitude) towards the pole.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] This relationship is only approximate, however, since local factors such as proximity to oceans can drastically modify the climate.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] In the alpine tundra, trees cannot tolerate the environmental conditions (usually cold temperatures, extreme snowpack, or associated lack of available moisture).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Typical high-elevation growing seasons range from 45 to 90 days, with average summer temperatures near 10 °C (50 °F).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Growing season temperatures frequently fall below freezing, and frost occurs throughout the growing season in many areas.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Precipitation occurs mainly as winter snow, but soil water availability is highly variable with season, location, and topography.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] For example, snowfields commonly accumulate on the lee sides of ridges while ridgelines may remain nearly snow free due to redistribution by wind.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Some alpine habitats may be up to 70% snow free in winter.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] High winds are common in alpine ecosystems, and can cause significant soil erosion and be physically and physiologically detrimental to plants.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Also, wind coupled with high solar radiation can promote extremely high rates of evaporation and transpiration.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] There have been several attempts at quantifying what constitutes an alpine climate.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Climatologist Wladimir Köppen demonstrated a relationship between the Arctic and Antarctic tree lines and the 10 °C summer isotherm; i.e., places where the average temperature in the warmest calendar month of the year is below 10 °C cannot support forests.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] See Köppen climate classification for more information.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] In 1947, Holdridge improved on these schemes, by defining biotemperature: the mean annual temperature, where all temperatures below 0 °C are treated as 0 °C (because it makes no difference to plant life, being dormant).
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] If the mean biotemperature is between 1.5 and 3 °C (34.7 and 37.4 °F), Holdridge quantifies the climate as alpine.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Since the habitat of alpine vegetation is subject to intense radiation, wind, cold, snow, and ice, it grows close to the ground and consists mainly of perennial grasses, sedges, and forbs.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Perennial herbs (including grasses, sedges, and low woody or semi-woody shrubs) dominate the alpine landscape; they have much more root and rhizome biomass than that of shoots, leaves, and flowers.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] The roots and rhizomes not only function in water and nutrient absorption but also play a very important role in over-winter carbohydrate storage.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Annual plants are rare in this ecosystem and usually are only a few inches tall, with weak root systems.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Other common plant life-forms include prostrate shrubs; tussock-forming graminoids; cushion plants; and cryptogams, such as bryophytes and lichens.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Relative to lower elevation areas in the same region, alpine regions have a high rate of endemism and a high diversity of plant species.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] This taxonomic diversity can be attributed to geographical isolation, climate changes, glaciation, microhabitat differentiation, and different histories of migration or evolution or both.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] These phenomena contribute to plant diversity by introducing new flora and favoring adaptations, both of new species and the dispersal of pre-existing species.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Plants have adapted to the harsh alpine environment.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Cushion plants, looking like ground-hugging clumps of moss, escape the strong winds blowing a few inches above them.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Many flowering plants of the alpine tundra have dense hairs on stems and leaves to provide wind protection or red-colored pigments capable of converting the sun's light rays into heat.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Some plants take two or more years to form flower buds, which survive the winter below the surface and then open and produce fruit with seeds in the few weeks of summer.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] In various areas of alpine tundra, woody plant encroachment is observed.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Alpine areas are unique because of the severity and complexity of their environmental conditions.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Very small changes in topography – as small as 1 foot (0.3 m) or less – may mean the difference between a windswept area or an area of snow accumulation, changing the potential productivity and plant community drastically.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Between these extremes of drought versus saturation, several intermediate environments may exist all within a few yards of each other, depending on topography, substrate, and climate.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Alpine vegetation generally occurs in a mosaic of small patches with widely differing environmental conditions.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Vegetation types vary from cushion and rosette plants on the ridges and in the rock crannies; to herbaceous and grassy vegetation along the slopes; dwarf shrubs with grasses and forbs below the melting snowdrifts; and sedges, grasses, low shrubs, and mosses in the bogs and along the brooks.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Alpine meadows form where sediments from the weathering of rocks has produced soils well-developed enough to support grasses and sedges.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Non-flowering lichens cling to rocks and soil.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Their enclosed algal cells can photosynthesize at any temperature above 0 °C (32 °F), and the outer fungal layers can absorb more than their own weight in water.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] The adaptations for survival of drying winds and cold may make tundra vegetation seem very hardy, but in some respects the tundra is very fragile.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Repeated footsteps often destroy tundra plants, allowing exposed soil to blow away; recovery may take hundreds of years.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] The characteristic aroma of many alpine meadows in the European Alps during summer is significantly influenced by the volatile organic compounds (VOCs) emitted by dominant plant species.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Because alpine tundra is located in various widely separated regions of the Earth, there is no animal species common to all areas of alpine tundra.
[src:ahklun-mountains/alpine-tundra] Some animals of alpine tundra environments include the kea, marmot, mountain goat, bighorn sheep, chinchilla, Himalayan tahr, yak, snow leopard, and pika.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers build dams and lodges using tree branches, vegetation, rocks and mud; they chew down trees for building material.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Dams restrict water flow, forming ponds.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Lodges, which are usually built in ponds, serve as shelters.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Their infrastructure creates wetlands used by many other species, and because of their effect on other organisms in the ecosystem, beavers are considered a keystone species.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Adult males and females live in monogamous pairs with their offspring.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] After their first year, the young help their parents repair dams and lodges; older siblings may also help raise newly born offspring.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers hold territories and mark them using scent mounds made of mud, debris, and castoreum—a liquid substance excreted through the beaver's urethra-based castor sacs.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers can also recognize their kin by their anal gland secretions and are more likely to tolerate them as neighbors.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Historically, beavers have been hunted for their fur, meat, and castoreum.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Castoreum has been used in medicine, perfume, and food flavoring; beaver pelts have been a major driver of the fur trade.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Before protections began in the 19th and early 20th centuries, overhunting had nearly exterminated both species.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Their populations have since rebounded, and they are listed as species of least concern by the IUCN Red List of mammals.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] In human culture, the beaver symbolizes industriousness, especially in connection with construction; it is the national animal of Canada.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The English word *beaver* comes from the Old English word *beofor* or *befor* and is connected to the German word *biber* and the Dutch word *bever*.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The ultimate origin of the word is an Indo-European root for 'brown'.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Cognates of *beaver* are the source for several European placenames, including those of Beverley, Bièvres, Biberbach, Biebrich, Bibra, Bibern, Bibrka, Bobr, Bober, Bóbrka, Bjurholm, Bjurälven, and Bjurum.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The genus name *Castor* has its origin in the Greek word κάστωρ *kastōr* and translates as 'beaver'.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Carl Linnaeus coined the genus name *Castor* as well as the specific (species) epithet *fiber* for the Eurasian species.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] German zoologist Heinrich Kuhl coined *C. canadensis* in 1820.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Many scientists considered both names synonymous for one same species until the 1970s, when chromosomal evidence became available confirming both as separate where the Eurasian has 48 chromosomes, while the North American has 40.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The difference in chromosome numbers prevents them from interbreeding.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Twenty-five subspecies have been classified for *C. canadensis*, and nine have been classified for *C. fiber*.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] There are two extant species: the North American beaver (*Castor canadensis*) and the Eurasian beaver (*C. fiber*).
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The Eurasian beaver is slightly longer and has a more lengthened skull, triangular nasal cavities (as opposed to the square ones of the North American species), a lighter fur color, and a narrower tail.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers belong to the rodent suborder Castorimorpha, along with Heteromyidae (kangaroo rats and kangaroo mice), and the gophers.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Modern beavers are the only extant members of the family Castoridae.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] They originated in North America in the late Eocene and colonized Eurasia via the Bering Land Bridge in the early Oligocene, coinciding with the *Grande Coupure*, a time of significant changes in animal species around 33 million years ago (myr).
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Members of the subfamily *Palaeocastorinae* appeared in late-Oligocene North America.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] This group consisted primarily of smaller animals with relatively large front legs, a flattened skull, and a reduced tail—all features of a fossorial (burrowing) lifestyle.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] In the early Miocene (about 24 mya), castorids evolved a semiaquatic lifestyle.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Members of the subfamily Castoroidinae are considered to be a sister group to modern beavers, and included giants like *Castoroides* of North America and *Trogontherium* of Eurasia.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Fossils of one genus in Castoroidinae, *Dipoides*, have been found near piles of chewed wood, though *Dipoides* appears to have been an inferior woodcutter compared to *Castor*.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Researchers suggest that modern beavers and Castoroidinae shared a bark-eating common ancestor.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Dam and lodge-building likely developed from bark-eating, and allowed beavers to survive in the harsh winters of the subarctic.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] There is no conclusive evidence for this behavior occurring in non-*Castor* species.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The genus *Castor* likely originated in Eurasia.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The earliest fossil remains appear to be *C. neglectus*, found in Germany and dated 12–10 mya.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Mitochondrial DNA studies place the common ancestor of the two living species at around 8 mya.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The ancestors of the North American beaver would have crossed the Bering Land Bridge around 7.5 mya.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] *Castor* may have competed with members of Castoroidinae, which led to niche differentiation.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The fossil species *C. praefiber* was likely an ancestor of the Eurasian beaver.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] *C. californicus* from the Early Pleistocene of North America was similar to but larger than the extant North American beaver.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers are the second-largest living rodents, after capybaras.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Males and females are almost identical externally.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Their bodies are streamlined like marine mammals and their robust build allows them to pull heavy loads.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] A beaver coat has 12,000–23,000 hairs/cm2 (77,000–148,000 hairs/in2) and functions to keep the animal warm, to help it float in water, and to protect it against predators.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Guard hairs are 5–6 cm (2.0–2.4 in) long and typically reddish brown, but can range from yellowish brown to nearly black.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The underfur is 2–3 cm (0.8–1.2 in) long and dark gray.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers have large skulls with powerful chewing muscles.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] They have four chisel-shaped incisors that continue to grow throughout their lives.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The incisors are covered in a thick enamel that is colored orange or reddish-brown by iron compounds.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The lower incisors have roots that are almost as long as the entire lower jaw.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers have one premolar and three molars on all four sides of the jaws, adding up to 20 teeth.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The molars have meandering ridges for grinding woody material.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The eyes, ears and nostrils are arranged so that they can remain above water while the rest of the body is submerged.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The nostrils and ears have valves that close underwater, while nictitating membranes cover the eyes.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] To protect the larynx and trachea from water flow, the epiglottis is contained within the nasal cavity instead of the throat.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] In addition, the back of the tongue can rise and create a waterproof seal.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] A beaver's lips can close behind the incisors, preventing water from entering their mouths as they cut and bite onto things while submerged.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The beaver's front feet are dexterous, allowing them to grasp and manipulate objects and food, as well as dig.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The hind feet are larger and have webbing between the toes, and the second innermost toe has a "double nail" used for grooming.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers can swim at 8 km/h (5 mph); only their webbed hind feet are used to swim, while the front feet fold under the chest.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] On the surface, the hind limbs thrust one after the other; while underwater, they move at the same time.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers are awkward on land but can move quickly when they feel threatened.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] They can carry objects while walking on their hind legs.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The beaver's distinctive tail has a conical, muscular, hairy base; the remaining two-thirds of the appendage is flat and scaly.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The tail has multiple functions: it provides support for the animal when it is upright (such as when chewing down a tree), acts as a rudder when it is swimming, and stores fat for winter.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] It also has a countercurrent blood vessel system which allows the animal to lose heat in warm temperatures and retain heat in cold temperatures.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The beaver's sex organs are inside the body, and the male's penis has a cartilaginous baculum.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] They have only one opening, a cloaca, which is used for reproduction, scent-marking, defecation, and urination.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The cloaca evolved secondarily, as most mammals have lost this feature, and may reduce the area vulnerable to infection in dirty water.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The beaver's intestine is six times longer than its body, and the caecum is double the volume of its stomach.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Microorganisms in the caecum allow them to process around 30 percent of the cellulose they eat.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] A beaver defecates in the water, leaving behind balls of sawdust.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Female beavers have four mammary glands; these produce milk with 19 percent fat, a higher fat content than other rodents.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers have two pairs of glands: castor sacs, which are part of the urethra, and anal glands.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The castor sacs secrete castoreum, a liquid substance used mainly for marking territory.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Anal glands produce an oily substance which the beaver uses as a waterproof ointment for its coat.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The substance plays a role in individual and family recognition.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Anal secretions are darker in females than males among Eurasian beavers, while the reverse is true for the North American species.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Compared to many other rodents, a beaver's brain has a hypothalamus significantly smaller than the cerebrum; this indicates a relatively advanced brain with higher intelligence.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The cerebellum is large, allowing the animal to move within a three-dimensional space (such as underwater) similar to tree-climbing squirrels.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The neocortex is devoted mainly to touch and hearing.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Touch is more advanced in the lips and hands than the whiskers and tail.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Vision in the beaver is relatively poor; the beaver eye cannot see as well underwater as an otter.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers have a good sense of smell, which they use for detecting land predators and for inspecting scent marks, food, and other individuals.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers can hold their breath for as long as 15 minutes but typically remain underwater for no more than five or six minutes.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Dives typically last less than 30 seconds and are usually no more than 1 m (3 ft 3 in) deep.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] When diving, their heart rate decreases to 60 beats per minute, half its normal pace, and blood flow is directed more towards the brain.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] A beaver's body also has a high tolerance for carbon dioxide.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] When surfacing, the animal can replace 75 percent of the air in its lungs in one breath, compared to 15 percent for a human.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The IUCN Red List of mammals lists both beaver species as least concern.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The North American beaver is widespread throughout most of the United States and Canada and can be found in northern Mexico.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The species was introduced to Finland in 1937 (and then spread to northwestern Russia) and to Tierra del Fuego, Patagonia, in 1946.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] As of 2019, the introduced population of North American beavers in Finland has been moving closer to the habitat of the Eurasian beaver.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Historically, the North American beaver was trapped and nearly extirpated because its fur was highly sought after.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Protections have allowed the beaver population on the continent to rebound to an estimated 6–12 million by the late 20th century; still far lower than the originally estimated 60–400 million North American beavers before the fur trade.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The introduced population in Tierra del Fuego is estimated at 35,000–50,000 individuals as of 2016.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The Eurasian beaver's range historically included much of Eurasia, but was decimated by hunting by the early 20th century.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] In Europe, beavers were reduced to fragmented populations, with combined population numbers being estimated at 1,200 individuals for the Rhône of France, the Elbe in Germany, southern Norway, the Neman river and Dnieper Basin in Belarus, and the Voronezh river in Russia.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The beaver has since recolonized parts of its former range, aided by conservation policies and reintroductions.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beaver populations now range across western, central, and eastern Europe, and western Russia and the Scandinavian Peninsula.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beginning in 2009, beavers have been successfully reintroduced to parts of Great Britain.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] In 2020, the total Eurasian beaver population in Europe was estimated at over one million.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Small native populations are also present in Mongolia and northwestern China.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] In 2016 their numbers were estimated at 150 and 700, respectively.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Under New Zealand's Hazardous Substances and New Organisms Act 1996, beavers are classed as a "prohibited new organism" preventing them from being introduced into the country.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers live in freshwater ecosystems such as rivers, streams, lakes and ponds.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Water is the most important component of beaver habitat; they swim and dive in it, and it provides them refuge from land predators.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] It also restricts access to their homes and allows them to move building objects more easily.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers prefer slower moving streams, typically with a gradient (steepness) of one percent, though they have been recorded using streams with gradients as high as 15 percent.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers are found in wider streams more often than in narrower ones.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] They also prefer areas with no regular flooding and may abandon a location for years after a significant flood.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers typically select flat landscapes with diverse vegetation close to the water.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] North American beavers prefer trees being 60 m (200 ft) or less from the water, but will roam several hundred meters to find more.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers have also been recorded in mountainous areas.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Dispersing beavers will use certain habitats temporarily before finding their ideal home.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] These include small streams, temporary swamps, ditches, and backyards.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] These sites lack important resources, so the animals do not stay there permanently.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers have increasingly settled at or near human-made environments, including agricultural areas, suburbs, golf courses, and shopping malls.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers have an herbivorous and a generalist diet.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] During the spring and summer, they mainly feed on herbaceous plant material such as leaves, roots, herbs, ferns, grasses, sedges, water lilies, water shields, rushes, and cattails.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] During the fall and winter, they eat more bark and cambium of woody plants; tree and shrub species consumed include aspen, birch, oak, dogwood, willow and alder.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] There is some disagreement about why beavers select specific woody plants; some research has shown that beavers more frequently select species which are more easily digested, while others suggest beavers principally forage based on stem size.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers may cache their food for the winter, piling wood in the deepest part of their pond where it cannot be reached by other browsers.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] This cache is known as a "raft"; when the top becomes frozen, it creates a "cap".
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The beaver accesses the raft by swimming under the ice.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Many populations of Eurasian beaver do not make rafts, but forage on land during winter.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers need trees and shrubs to use as building material for dams, which restrict flowing water to create a pond for them to live in, and for lodges, which act as shelters and refuges from predators and the elements.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Without such material, beavers dig burrows into a bank to live.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Dam construction begins in late summer or early fall, and they repair them whenever needed.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers can cut down trees up to 15 cm (6 in) wide in less than 50 minutes.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Thicker trees, at 25 cm (10 in) wide or more, may not fall for hours.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] When chewing down a tree, beavers switch between biting with the left and right side of the mouth.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Tree branches are then cut and carried to their destination with the powerful jaw and neck muscles.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Other building materials, like mud and rocks, are held by the forelimbs and tucked between the chin and chest.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers start building dams when they hear running water, and the sound of a leak in a dam triggers them to repair it.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] To build a dam, beavers stack up relatively long and thick logs between the banks.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Heavy rocks keep them stable, and grass is packed between them.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers continue to pile on more material until the dam slopes in a direction facing upstream.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Dams can range in height from 20 cm (8 in) to 3 m (10 ft) and can stretch from 0.3 m (0.98 ft) to several hundred meters long.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beaver dams are more effective in trapping and slowly leaking water than man-made concrete dams.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Lake-dwelling beavers do not need to build dams.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers make two types of lodges: bank lodges and open-water lodges.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Bank lodges are burrows dug along the shore and covered in sticks while the more complex freestanding, open-water lodges are built over a platform of piled-up sticks.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The lodge is mostly sealed with mud, except for a hole at the top which acts as an air vent.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Both types are accessed by underwater entrances.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The above-water space inside the lodge is known as the "living chamber", and a "dining area" may exist close to the water entrance.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Families routinely clean out old plant material and bring in new material.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] North American beavers build more open-water lodges than Eurasian beavers.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beaver lodges built by new settlers are typically small and sloppy.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] More experienced families can build structures with a height of 2 m (6 ft 7 in) and an above-water diameter of 6 m (20 ft).
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] A lodge sturdy enough to withstand the coming winter can be finished in just two nights.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Both lodge types can be present at a beaver site.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers tend to use bank lodges to keep cool during the summer and use open-water lodges during the winter.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The air vent provides ventilation, and newly added carbon dioxide can be cleared in an hour.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The lodge remains consistent in oxygen and carbon dioxide levels from season to season.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers in some areas will dig canals connected to their ponds.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The canals fill with groundwater and give beavers access and easier transport of resources, as well as allow them to escape predators.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] These canals can stretch up to 1 m (3 ft 3 in) wide, 0.5 m (1 ft 8 in) deep, and over 0.5 km (0.3 mi) long.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] It has been hypothesized that beavers' canals are not only transportation routes but an extension of their "central place" around the lodge and/or food cache.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] As they drag wood across the land, beavers leave behind trails or "slides", which they reuse when moving new material.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Images of a beaver dam over a four-month period.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The beaver works as an ecosystem engineer and keystone species, as its activities can have a great impact on the landscape and biodiversity of an area.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Aside from humans, few other extant animals appear to do more to shape their environment.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] When building dams, beavers alter the paths of streams and rivers, allowing for the creation of extensive wetland habitats.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] In one study, beavers were associated with large increases in open-water areas.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] When beavers returned to an area, 160% more open water was available during droughts than in previous years, when they were absent.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beaver dams also lead to higher water tables in mineral soil environments and in wetlands such as peatlands.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] In peatlands particularly, their dams stabilize the constantly changing water levels, leading to greater carbon storage.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beaver ponds, and the wetlands that succeed them, remove sediments and pollutants from waterways, and can stop the loss of important soils.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] These ponds can increase the productivity of freshwater ecosystems by accumulating nitrogen in sediments.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beaver activity can affect the temperature of the water; in northern latitudes, ice thaws earlier in the warmer beaver-dammed waters.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers may contribute to climate change.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] In Arctic areas, the floods they create can cause permafrost to thaw, releasing methane into the atmosphere.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] As wetlands are formed and riparian habitats are enlarged, aquatic plants colonize the newly available watery habitat.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] One study in the Adirondacks found that beaver engineering led to an increase of more than 33 percent in herbaceous plant diversity along the water's edge.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Another study in semiarid eastern Oregon found that the width of riparian vegetation on stream banks increased several-fold as beaver dams watered previously dry terraces adjacent to the stream.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Riparian ecosystems in arid areas appear to sustain more plant life when beaver dams are present.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beaver ponds act as a refuge for riverbank plants during wildfires, and provide them with enough moisture to resist such fires.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Introduced beavers at Tierra del Fuego have been responsible for destroying the indigenous forest.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Unlike trees in North America, many trees in South America cannot grow back after being cut down.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beaver activity impacts communities of aquatic invertebrates.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Damming typically leads to an increase of slow or motionless water species, like dragonflies, oligochaetes, snails, and mussels.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] This is to the detriment of rapid water species like black flies, stoneflies, and net-spinning caddisflies.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beaver floodings create more dead trees, providing more habitat for terrestrial invertebrates like *Drosophila* flies and bark beetles, which live and breed in dead wood.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The presence of beavers can increase wild salmon and trout populations, and the average size of these fishes.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] These species use beaver habitats for spawning, overwintering, feeding, and as havens from changes in water flow.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The positive effects of beaver dams on fish appear to outweigh the negative effects, such as blocking of migration.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beaver ponds have been shown to be beneficial to frog populations by protecting areas for larvae to mature in warm water.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The stable waters of beaver ponds also provide ideal habitat for freshwater turtles.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers help waterfowl by creating increased areas of water.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The widening of the riparian zone associated with beaver dams has been shown to increase the abundance and diversity of birds favoring the water's edge, an impact that may be especially important in semi-arid climates.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Fish-eating birds use beaver ponds for foraging, and in some areas, certain species appear more frequently at sites where beavers were active than at sites with no beaver activity.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] In a study of Wyoming streams and rivers, watercourses with beavers had 75 times as many ducks as those without.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] As trees are drowned by rising beaver impoundments, they become an ideal habitat for woodpeckers, which carve cavities that may be later used by other bird species.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beaver-caused ice thawing in northern latitudes allows Canada geese to nest earlier.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Other semi-aquatic mammals, such as water voles, muskrats, minks, and otters, will shelter in beaver lodges.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beaver modifications to streams in Poland create habitats favorable to bat species that forage at the water surface and "prefer moderate vegetation clutter".
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Large herbivores, such as some deer species, benefit from beaver activity as they can access vegetation from fallen trees and ponds.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Felids, canids, and bears may prey upon them.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers are protected from predators when in their lodges, and prefer to stay near water.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Parasites of the beaver include the bacteria *Francisella tularensis*, which causes tularemia; the protozoan *Giardia duodenalis*, which causes giardiasis (beaver fever); and the beaver beetle and mites of the genus *Schizocarpus*.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] They have also been recorded to be infected with the rabies virus.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] North American beaver family, with the center pair grooming one another.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers are mainly nocturnal and crepuscular, and spend the daytime in their shelters.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] In northern latitudes, beaver activity is decoupled from the 24-hour cycle during the winter, and may last as long as 29 hours.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] They do not hibernate during winter, and spend much of their time in their lodges.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The core of beaver social organization is the family, which is composed of an adult male and an adult female in a monogamous pair and their offspring.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beaver families can have as many as ten members; groups about this size require multiple lodges.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Mutual grooming and play fighting maintain bonds between family members, and aggression between them is uncommon.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Adult beavers mate with their partners, though partner replacement appears to be common.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] A beaver that loses its partner will wait for another one to come by.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Estrus cycles begin in late December and peak in mid-January.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Females may have two to four estrus cycles per season, each lasting 12–24 hours.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The pair typically mate in the water and to a lesser extent in the lodge, for half a minute to three minutes.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Up to four young, or kits, are born in spring and summer, after a three or four-month gestation.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Newborn beavers are precocial with a full fur coat, and can open their eyes within days of birth.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Their mother is the primary caretaker, while their father maintains the territory.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Older siblings from a previous litter also play a role.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] After they are born, the kits spend their first one to two months in the lodge.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Kits suckle for as long as three months, but can eat solid food within their second week and rely on their parents and older siblings to bring it to them.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Eventually, beaver kits explore outside the lodge and forage on their own, but may follow an older relative and hold onto their backs.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] After their first year, young beavers help their families with construction.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers sexually mature around the ages of 1.5–3 years.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] They become independent at two years old, but remain with their parents for an extra year or more during times of food shortage, high population density, or drought.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers typically disperse from their parental colonies during the spring or when the winter snow melts.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] They often travel less than 5 km (3 mi), but long-distance dispersals are not uncommon when previous colonizers have already exploited local resources.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers are able to travel greater distances when free-flowing water is available.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Individuals may meet their mates during the dispersal stage, and the pair travel together.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] It may take them weeks or months to reach their final destination; longer distances may require several years.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers establish and defend territories along the banks of their ponds, which may be 1–7 km (0.6–4.3 mi) in length.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers mark their territories by constructing scent mounds made of mud and vegetation, scented with castoreum.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Those with many territorial neighbors create more scent mounds.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Scent marking increases in spring, during the dispersal of yearlings, to deter interlopers.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers are generally intolerant of intruders and fights may result in deep bites to the sides, rump, and tail.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] They exhibit a behavior known as the "dear enemy effect"; a territory-holder will investigate and become familiar with the scents of its neighbors and react more aggressively to the scents of strangers passing by.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers are also more tolerant of individuals that are their kin.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] They recognize them by using their keen sense of smell to detect differences in the composition of anal gland secretions.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Anal gland secretion profiles are more similar among relatives than unrelated individuals.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers within a family greet each other with whines.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Kits will attract the attention of adults with mews, squeaks, and cries.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Defensive beavers produce a hissing growl and gnash their teeth.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Tail slaps, which involve a beaver hitting the water surface with its tail, serve as alarm signals warning other beavers of a potential threat.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] An adult's tail slap is more successful in alerting others, who will escape into the lodge or deeper water.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Juveniles have not yet learned the proper use of a tail slap, and hence are normally ignored.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Eurasian beavers have been recorded using a territorial "stick display", which involves individuals holding up a stick and bouncing in shallow water.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers sometimes come into conflict with humans over land use; individual beavers may be labeled as "nuisance beavers".
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers can damage crops, timber stocks, roads, ditches, gardens, and pastures via gnawing, eating, digging, and flooding.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] They occasionally attack humans and domestic pets, particularly when infected with rabies, in defense of their territory, or when they feel threatened.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Some of these attacks have been fatal, including at least one human death.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers can spread giardiasis ('beaver fever') by infecting surface waters, though outbreaks are more commonly caused by human activity.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Flow devices, like beaver pipes, are used to manage beaver flooding, while fencing and hardware cloth protect trees and shrubs from beaver damage.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] If necessary, hand tools, heavy equipment, or explosives are used to remove dams.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Hunting, trapping, and relocation may be permitted as forms of population control and for removal of individuals.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The governments of Argentina and Chile have authorized the trapping of invasive beavers in hopes of eliminating them.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The ecological importance of beavers has led to cities like Seattle designing their parks and green spaces to accommodate the animals.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The Martinez beavers became famous in the mid-2000s for their role in improving the ecosystem of Alhambra Creek in Martinez, California.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Zoos have displayed beavers since at least the 19th century, though not commonly.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] In captivity, beavers have been used for entertainment, fur harvesting, and for reintroduction into the wild.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Captive beavers require access to water, substrate for digging, and artificial shelters.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Archibald Stansfeld "Grey Owl" Belaney pioneered beaver conservation in the early 20th century.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Belaney wrote several books, and was first to professionally film beavers in their environment.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] In 1931, he moved to a log cabin in Prince Albert National Park, where he was the "caretaker of park animals" and raised a beaver pair and their four offspring.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Dorothy Burney Richards, inspired by Belaney, lived with beavers in her home at Beaversprite.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] with the beaver depicted as biting off its testicles.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers have been hunted, trapped, and exploited for their fur, meat, and castoreum.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Since the animals typically stayed in one place, trappers could easily find them and could kill entire families in a lodge.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Many pre-modern people mistakenly thought that castoreum was produced by the testicles or that the castor sacs of the beaver were its testicles, and females were hermaphrodites.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Aesop's Fables describes beavers chewing off their testicles to preserve themselves from hunters, which is impossible because a beaver's testicles are internal.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] This myth persisted for centuries, and was corrected by French physician Guillaume Rondelet in the 1500s.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers have historically been hunted and captured using deadfalls, snares, nets, bows and arrows, spears, clubs, firearms, and leg-hold traps.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Castoreum was used for a variety of medical purposes; Pliny the Elder promoted it as a treatment for stomach problems, flatulence, seizures, sciatica, vertigo, and epilepsy.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] He stated it could stop hiccups when mixed with vinegar, toothaches if mixed with oil (by administering into the ear opening on the same side as the tooth), and could be used as an antivenom.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The substance has traditionally been prescribed to treat hysteria in women, which was believed to have been caused by a "toxic" womb.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Castoreum's properties have been credited to the accumulation of salicylic acid from willow and aspen trees in the beaver's diet, and has a physiological effect comparable to aspirin.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Today, the medical use of castoreum has declined and is limited mainly to homeopathy.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The substance is also used as an ingredient in perfumes and tinctures, and as a flavouring in food and drinks.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Various Native American groups have historically hunted beavers for food, they preferred its meat more than other red meats because of its higher calorie and fat content, and the animals remained plump in winter when they were most hunted.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] In medieval Europe, the Catholic Church considered the beaver to be part mammal and part fish, and allowed followers to eat the scaly, fishlike tail on meatless Fridays during Lent.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beaver tails were thus highly prized in Europe; they were described by French naturalist Pierre Belon as tasting like a "nicely dressed eel".
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beaver pelts were used to make hats; felters would remove the guard hairs.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The number of pelts needed depended on the type of hat, with Cavalier and Puritan hats requiring more fur than top hats.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] In the late 16th century, Europeans began to deal in North American furs due to the lack of taxes or tariffs on the continent and the decline of fur-bearers at home.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beaver pelts caused or contributed to the Beaver Wars, King William's War, and the French and Indian War; the trade made John Jacob Astor and the owners of the North West Company very wealthy.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] For Europeans in North America, the fur trade was a driver of the exploration and westward exploration on the continent and contact with native peoples, who traded with them.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The fur trade peaked between 1860 and 1870, when over 150,000 beaver pelts were purchased annually by the Hudson's Bay Company and fur companies in the United States.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The contemporary global fur trade is not as profitable due to conservation, anti-fur and animal rights campaigns.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The beaver has been used to represent productivity, trade, tradition, masculinity, and respectability.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] References to the beaver's skills are reflected in everyday language.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The English verb "to beaver" means working with great effort and being "as busy as a beaver"; a "beaver intellect" refers to a way of thinking that is slow and honest.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Though it typically has a wholesome image, the beaver's name has been used as a sexual term for the human vulva.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Native American myths emphasize the beaver's skill and industriousness.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] In the mythology of the Haida, beavers are descended from the Beaver-Woman, who built a dam on a stream next to their cabin while her husband was out hunting and gave birth to the first beavers.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] In a Cree story, the Great Beaver and its dam caused a world flood.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Other tales involve beavers using their tree chewing skills against an enemy.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers have been featured as companions in some stories, including a Lakota tale where a young woman flees from her evil husband with the aid of her pet beaver.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Europeans have traditionally thought of beavers as fantastical animals due to their amphibious nature.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] They depicted them with exaggerated tusk-like teeth, dog- or pig-like bodies, fish tails, and visible testicles.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] French cartographer Nicolas de Fer illustrated beavers building a dam at Niagara Falls, fantastically depicting them like human builders.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Beavers have also appeared in literature such as Dante Alighieri's *Divine Comedy* and the writings of Athanasius Kircher, who wrote that on Noah's Ark the beavers were housed near a water-filled tub that was also used by mermaids and otters.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The beaver has long been associated with Canada, appearing on the first pictorial postage stamp issued in the Canadian colonies in 1851 as the so-called "Three-Penny Beaver".
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] It was declared the national animal in 1975.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The five-cent coin, the coat of arms of the Hudson's Bay Company, and the logos for Parks Canada and Roots Canada use its image.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] Frank and Gordon are two fictional beavers that appeared in Bell Canada's advertisements between 2005 and 2008.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] However, the beaver's status as a rodent has made it controversial, and it was not chosen to be on the Arms of Canada in 1921.
[src:ahklun-mountains/beaver] The beaver has commonly been used to represent Canada in political cartoons, typically to signify it as a friendly but relatively weak nation.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] The Latin specific epithet *mariana* means "of the Virgin Mary".
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] Natural hybridization occurs regularly with the closely related *P. rubens* (red spruce) and very rarely with *P. glauca* (white spruce).
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] It differs from *P. glauca* in having a dense cover of small hairs on the bark of young branch tips, an often darker reddish-brown bark, shorter needles, smaller and rounder cones, and a preference for wetter lowland areas.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] Numerous differences in details of its needle and pollen morphology also exist but require careful microscopic examination to detect.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] From true firs, such as *Abies balsamea* (balsam fir), it differs in having pendulous cones, persistent woody leaf-bases, and four-angled needles, arranged all round the shoots.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] Due to the large difference between heartwood and sapwood moisture content, it is easy to distinguish these two wood characteristics in ultrasound images, which are widely used as a nondestructive technique to assess the internal condition of the tree and avoid useless log breakdown.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] Older taxonomic synonyms include *A. mariana*, *P. brevifolia*, or *P. nigra*.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] In swamp and muskeg it shows progressively slower growth rates from the edges toward the centre.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] The roots are shallow and wide spreading, resulting in susceptibility to windthrow.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] In the northern part of its range, ice pruned asymmetric black spruce are often seen with diminished foliage on the windward side.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] Tilted trees colloquially called "drunken trees" are associated with thawing of permafrost.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] In the southern portion of its range it is found primarily on wet organic soils, but farther north its abundance on uplands increases.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] In the Great Lakes region it is most abundant in peat bogs and swamps, also on transitional sites between peatlands and uplands.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] In these areas it is rare on uplands, except in isolated areas of northern Minnesota and the Upper Peninsula of Michigan.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] Most stands are even-aged due to frequent fire intervals in black spruce forests.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] It commonly grows in pure stands on organic soils and in mixed stands on mineral soils.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] It is tolerant of nutrient-poor soils and is commonly found on poorly drained acidic peatlands.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] It is considered a climax species over most of its range; however, some ecologists question whether black spruce forests truly attain climax because fires usually occur at 50 to 150 year intervals, while "stable" conditions may not be attained for several hundred years.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] The frequent fire return interval, a natural fire ecology, perpetuates numerous successional communities.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] Throughout boreal North America, *Betula papyrifera* (paper birch) and *Populus tremuloides* (quaking aspen) are successional hardwoods that frequently invade burns in black spruce.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] Black spruce typically seeds in promptly after fire and with the continued absence of fire eventually dominates the hardwoods.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] Black spruce is a pioneer that invades the sphagnum mat in filled-lake bogs, though often preceded slightly by *Larix laricina* (tamarack).
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] Black spruce frequently out-competes shade-intolerant tamarack in the course of bog succession.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] However, as the peat soil is gradually elevated by the accumulation of organic matter and the fertility of the site improves, balsam fir and northern white cedar (*Thuja occidentalis*) eventually replace black spruce and tamarack.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] On drier sites following fires, black spruce can take over stands of faster growing jack pine (*Pinus banksiana*) by virtue of its ability to grow in partially shaded conditions which inhibit pine seedlings.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] But black spruce seedlings are intolerant to the low light and low moisture conditions under mature spruce stands.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] Balsam fir and northern white cedar, both more understory-tolerant species with deeper taproots, survive and eventually succeed the spruce in the absence of fire.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] The spruce budworm, a moth larva, causes defoliation which kills trees if it occurs several years in a row, though black spruce is less susceptible than white spruce or balsam fir.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] Trees most at risk are those growing along with balsam fir and white spruce.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] Numerous cultivars have been selected for use in parks and gardens.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] The cultivar *P. mariana* 'Nana' is a dwarf form which has gained the Royal Horticultural Society's Award of Garden Merit.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] Picea mariana is known to hybridize with Serbian spruce, *Picea omorika*.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] The hybrid is *Picea machala*, and hybrids with Sitka spruce are known as well.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] Black spruce is the provincial tree of Newfoundland and Labrador.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] The timber is of low value due to the small size of the trees, but it is an important source of pulpwood and the primary source of it in Canada.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] Fast-food chopsticks are often made from black spruce.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] It is increasingly being used for making cross laminated timber by companies such as Nordic Structures, which allows the high strength due to the tight growth rings to be assembled into larger timbers.
[src:ahklun-mountains/black-spruce] Along with red spruce, it has also been used to make spruce gum and spruce beer.
